 Macedonia (The Department of Western Macedonia today) (in Greek) |publisher=Society for Macedonian Studies,Thessaloniki  |year=1989|isbn=960-7265-01-7|url=http://media.ems.gr/ekdoseis/makedoniki_bibliothiki/ekd_makb_samsaris_070.pdf}}\n*{{cite book |last=Souvatzi|first=Stella G.|title=A Social Archaeology of Households in Neolithic Greece : an Anthropological Approach |publisher=Cambridge University Press  |year=2008|isbn=978-0-521-83689-0}}\n*{{cite book |last=Treadgold |first=Warren |title=Byzantium and Its Army, 284&ndash;1081 |publisher=Stanford University Press |year=1995 |isbn=0-8047-3163-2 |chapter=The Roman Army's Second Millenium}}{{sic}}\n*{{cite book|first=Apostolos E.|last=Vacalopoulos|year=1973|title=History of Macedonia, 1354&ndash;1833 (translated by P. Megann)|publisher=Zeno Publishers|isbn=0-900834-89-7|url=http://www.promacedonia.org/en/av/}}\n*{{cite book|year=1997|title=Afieroma to N.G.L. Hammond|publisher=Society of Macedonian Studies|isbn=960-7265-36-X |last=Wardle|first=K.A.|chapter=The Prehistory of Northern Greece: a Geographical Perspective}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Macedonia (Greece)}}\n\n* [http://www.mathra.gr/ Ministry of the Interior \u2013 Deputy Minister for Macedonia\u2013Thrace] {{in lang|el}}\n* [http://www.pkm.gov.gr/ Region of Central Macedonia]\n* [http://www.pdm.gov.gr/ Region of Western Macedonia]\n* [http://www.pamth.gov.gr/ Region of Eastern Macedonia and Thrace]\n\n{{Greek Macedonia}}\n{{Geographic departments of Greece}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Macedonia (Greece)| ]]\n[[Category:Traditional geographic divisions of Greece]]\n[[Category:Politics of Greece]]\n[[Category:Northern Greece]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Greek region||Macedonia (disambiguation){{!}}Macedonia}}\n{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->| name                            = Macedonia\n| native_name                     = \u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\n| native_name_lang                = el\n| settlement_type                 = [[Geographic regions of Greece|Traditional region]] of [[Greece]]\n| image_flag                      = Flag of Greek Macedonia.svg\n| flag_size                       = x90px\n| flag_alt                        = Flag of Macedonia\n| image_seal                      = Vergina Sun WIPO.svg\n| seal_size                       = x90px\n| seal_alt                        = The Vergina Sun\n| seal_type                       = Vergina Sun\n| seal_link                       = Vergina Sun\n| anthem                          = \u00ab[[Famous Macedonia|\u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1 \u03be\u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae]]\u00bb<br />Makedonia Ksakousti<br />{{small|\"Famous Macedonia\"}}<br />{{center|}}\n| image_map                       = Location_map_of_Macedonia_(Greece).svg\n| map_alt                         = Macedonia (blue) within Greece\n| map_caption                     = Macedonia (blue) within Greece\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|40|45|N|22|54|E|region:GR_type:adm1st|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{GRE}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Administrative regions of Greece|Regions]]<ref>{{cite book |title= \u03a0.\u0394. 51/87 \"\u039a\u03b1\u03b8\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c6\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03ce\u03bd \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a7\u03ce\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf \u03c3\u03c7\u03b5\u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc \u03ba.\u03bb.\u03c0. \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c6\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0391\u03bd\u03ac\u03c0\u03c4\u03c5\u03be\u03b7\u03c2\" (Determination of the Regions of the Country for the planning etc. of the development of the regions) |publisher= Government Gazette |year=1987}}</ref>\n| subdivision_name1               = {{bulleted list |[[Eastern Macedonia and Thrace]] (in part)|[[Central Macedonia]]|[[Western Macedonia]]}}\n| established_title               = Established\n| established_date                = 1913<ref name=\"Britannica\">{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/354264/Macedonia |title=Macedonia |encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |publisher=www.britannica.com |accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref>\n| seat_type                       = Capital\n| seat                            = [[Thessaloniki]]\n| leader_party                    = {{nowrap|[[New Democracy (Greece)|New Democracy]]}}\n| leader_title                    = [[Deputy Minister for Macedonia and Thrace|Deputy Minister]]\n| leader_name                     = {{interlanguage link|Theodoros Karaoglou|el|\u0398\u03b5\u03cc\u03b4\u03c9\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03b1\u03c1\u03ac\u03bf\u03b3\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5}}\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_total_km2                  = 34,177\n| elevation_max_m                 = 2,917\n| elevation_max_ft                = 9,570\n| elevation_max_point             = [[Mount Olympus]]\n| elevation_min_m                 = 0\n| elevation_min_ft                = 0\n| elevation_min_point             = [[Sea level]]\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"Mac Pop 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/show.do?dataset=demo_r_pjanind3&lang=en |title=Population: Structure indicators by NUTS 3 region |publisher=[[Eurostat]] |accessdate=27 January 2019 }}</ref>\n| population_total                = 2,382,857\n| population_as_of                = 2017\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = [[Macedonians (Greeks)|Macedonian]]\n| blank_name_sec1                 = GDP (PPP)<ref name=\"Eurostat GDP\">{{cite web |url=http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/show.do?dataset=nama_10r_3gdp&lang=en |title=Gross domestic product (GDP) at current market prices at NUTS level 3 |publisher=[[Eurostat]] |accessdate=27 January 2019 }}</ref>\n| blank_info_sec1                 = \u20ac38.17 billion {{nowrap|(${{toUSD|38.17|EUR|2014}} billion)}}\n| website                         = <!-- {{url|http://www.mathra.gr}} -->\n| footnotes                       = * The flag, Vergina Sun, and regional anthem are unofficial but their use is widespread.\n* Eastern Macedonia is part of the region of [[Eastern Macedonia and Thrace]].\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Macedonia''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=en-us-Macedonia.ogg|\u02cc|m|\u00e6|s|\u026a|\u02c8|d|o\u028a|n|i|\u0259}}; {{lang-el|\u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1}}, {{Lang|el-Latn|Makedhon\u00eda}} {{IPA-el|make\u00f0o\u02c8nia||Makedonia pronunciation.ogg|}}) is a [[geographic regions of Greece|geographic]] and administrative region of [[Greece]], in the southern [[Balkans]]. Macedonia is the largest and {{nowrap|second-most-populous}} Greek region, with a population of 2.38 million in 2017. The region is highly [[mountain]]ous, with most major urban centers such as [[Thessaloniki]] and [[Kavala]] being concentrated on its southern coastline. Together with [[Western Thrace|Thrace]], and sometimes also [[Thessaly]] and [[Epirus (region)|Epirus]], it is part of [[Northern Greece]]. Greek Macedonia encompasses entirely the southern part of the [[region of Macedonia]],<ref>Roy E. H. Mellor, ''Eastern Europe: A Geography of the Comecon Countries'', Macmillan International Higher Education, 1975, {{ISBN|1349155594}}, p. 62.</ref> making up 51% of the total area of the region. It also contains [[Mount Athos]], an autonomous monastic region of Greece. Macedonia forms part of Greece's [[border|national frontier]] with three countries: [[Bulgaria]] to the northeast, [[North Macedonia]] to the north, and [[Albania]] to the northwest.\n\nMacedonia incorporates most of the territories of ancient [[Macedonia (ancient kingdom)|Macedon]], a kingdom ruled by the [[Argead Dynasty|Argeads]], whose most celebrated members were [[Alexander the Great]] and his father [[Philip II of Macedon|Philip II]]. The name ''Macedonia'' was later applied to a number of widely-differing administrative areas in the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] and [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] empires, resulting in [[Macedonia (region)|modern geographical Macedonia]]. Even prior to the establishment of the modern Greek state in 1830 Macedonia was identified as a Greek province, albeit without clearly defined geographical borders.<ref name=\"Etairia Makedonikon Spoudon 1\">{{cite book |last1=Grigoriou |first1= Alexandros Ch. |last2=Chekimoglou |first2= Evangelos A. |script-title=el:\u0397 \u0398\u03b5\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03ba\u03b7 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03b7\u03b3\u03b7\u03c4\u03ce\u03bd 1430\u20131930 |trans-title=The Thessaloniki of Explorers 1430\u20131930 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=p6vdPgAACAAJ&dq=%CE%97+%CE%98%CE%B5%CF%83%CF%83%CE%B1%CE%BB%CE%BF%CE%BD%CE%AF%CE%BA%CE%B7+%CF%84%CF%89%CE%BD+%CE%A0%CE%B5%CF%81%CE%B9%CE%B7%CE%B3%CE%B7%CF%84%CF%8E%CE%BD |accessdate=2 August 2011 |year=2008 |publisher=\u0395\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03af\u03b1 \u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd \u03a3\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03b4\u03ce\u03bd |location=Thessaloniki |language=Greek |isbn=978-960-7265-91-3 |page=43 |quote=From Robert de Dreux's personal journals, 1669: Leaving a village named Baicui, we reached Thessaloniki, which is one of the most splendid cities of Macedonia and the whole of Greece.}}</ref><ref>\"The whole of Greece is divided into four great pashaliks; Tripolizza, Egripo or Neropont, Yanina, and Salonica. The pashalik of [\u2026] Salonica [comprises], the southern divisions of Macedonia. The north of Macedonia is governed by beys;\u2026\" Quoted from: Thomas Thornton, ''The Present State of Turkey'', London 1807, Vol. 2, p. 10, http://depts.washington.edu/cartah/text_archive/thornton/t2c5.shtml</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://depts.washington.edu/cartah/text_archive/thornton/page_images/t2c5_p010.jpg |title=Data |website=depts.washington.edu |format=JPG |access-date=2009-05-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420210151/http://depts.washington.edu/cartah/text_archive/thornton/page_images/t2c5_p010.jpg |archive-date=2016-04-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>\"The most fertile districts of Greece are Macedonia, Thessaly, and the eastern parts of Phocis and Boeotia.\" Quoted from: Conder, Josiah: ''The Modern Traveller, Volume the Fifteenth: Greece''. London : J.Duncan, 1830, Vol. 1, p. 12. [https://archive.org/stream/moderntraveller15condiala Archive.org]</ref><ref>\"There is some difficulty in prescribing the exact boundaries of the country properly called Greece. Formerly it included Macedonia, Peloponnesus, the Ionian Islands, Crete and a part of what is now called Albania. [...] The present divisions of Greece, adopted by the [1829] provisional government, are the following: Eastern Hellas, Western Hellas, Morea, Epirus, Thessaly, Macedonia, Crete, and the Islands. [\u2026] What proportion of Macedonia is considered as coming within the boundaries of Greece, we have no means of deciding\" Quoted from: John L. Comstock, ''History of the Greek Revolution compiled from official documents of the Greek government'', New York 1829, [https://archive.org/details/historygreekrev01comsgoog pages 5] and [https://archive.org/details/historygreekrev01comsgoog 6], [[Google Books]]</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=January 2018}} Modern Macedonia was established in 1913, in the aftermath of the [[Treaty of Bucharest (1913)|Treaty of Bucharest]] which ended the [[Balkan Wars]]. It continued as an administrative subdivision of Greece until the administrative reform of 1987, when it was divided into the regions of [[Western Macedonia]], [[Central Macedonia]], and part of the region of [[Eastern Macedonia and Thrace]], the latter containing also the whole Greek part of the region of Thrace.<ref>\u03a0.\u0394. 51/87 \"\u039a\u03b1\u03b8\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c6\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03ce\u03bd \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a7\u03ce\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf \u03c3\u03c7\u03b5\u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc \u03ba.\u03bb.\u03c0. \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c6\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0391\u03bd\u03ac\u03c0\u03c4\u03c5\u03be\u03b7\u03c2\" (''Determination of the Regions of the Country for the planning etc. of the development of the regions, [[Efimeris tis Kyverniseos]] \u03a6\u0395\u039a A 26/06.03.1987</ref>\n\nThe region remains an important economic centre for Greece. Macedonia accounts for the majority of Greece's agricultural production and is also a major contributor to the country's industrial and tourism sectors. [[Central Macedonia]] is Greece's {{nowrap|fourth-most-popular}} tourist region and the most popular destination that is not an [[island]].<ref name=\"Fig 2018\">{{cite web |url=http://www.statistics.gr/documents/20181/1515741/GreeceInFigures_2018Q4_EN.pdf/e64eb95a-766b-4540-847b-43dd555b5aa4 |publisher=[[Hellenic Statistical Authority]] |title=Greece in Figures 2018 |website=www.statistics.gr}}</ref> It is home to four [[List of World Heritage Sites in Greece|UNESCO World Heritage sites]], including [[Vergina|Aigai]], one of the ancient Macedonian capital cities. [[Pella]], which replaced Aigai as the capital of Macedon in the fourth century BC, is also located in Greek Macedonia.\n\n== Etymology ==\n{{Main|Macedonia (terminology)#Etymology}}\nThe name ''Macedonia'' derives from the {{Lang-el|\u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1}} (''{{transl|el|ISO|{{Audio|Makedonia pronunciation.ogg|Makedhon\u00eda|help=no}}}}''),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3D%2364599|title=\u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1 |work=A Greek-English Lexicon |publisher=[[Perseus Project]] |first1=Henry George |last1=Liddell |first2=Robert |last2=Scott}}</ref><ref name=\"Macedonia\">{{cite dictionary|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=Macedonia|title=Macedonia |last=Harper |first=Douglas |dictionary=[[Online Etymology Dictionary]]}}</ref> a [[Macedon|kingdom]] (later, [[Macedonia (region)|region]]) named after the [[ancient Macedonians]], who were the descendants of a [[Bronze-age]] Greek [[tribe]].<ref name=\"poulton'>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=j_NbmSoRsRcC&pg=PA1&dq=macedonia+is+greek#v=onepage&q=Macedones&f=false |title=Who are the Macedonians? |last=Poulton |first=Hugh |date=1995 |publisher=Hurst |isbn=9781850652380 |pages=44 |language=en}}</ref> Their name, {{Lang|el|\u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03cc\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2}} ({{Lang|el-Latn|Makedh\u00f3nes}}), is cognate to the [[Ancient Greek]] adjective [[Makednos|\u03bc\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2]] ({{Lang|el-Latn|makedhn\u00f3s}}), meaning \"tall, slim\".<ref name=\"Macedonia\" /> It was traditionally derived from the [[Indo-European root]] ''*mak-'', meaning 'long' or 'slender'. Linguist [[Robert S. P. Beekes]] supports the idea that both terms are of [[Pre-Greek substrate]] origin and cannot be explained in terms of [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] morphology.<ref>{{citation |first=Robert |last=Beekes |author-link=Pre-Greek substrate |title=Etymological Dictionary of Greek |volume=II |page=894 |publisher=Brill |year=2010 |location=Leiden, Boston}}</ref> However, Beekes' views are not mainstream and De Decker argues that his arguments are insufficient.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=De Decker |first1=Filip |title=AN ETYMOLOGICAL CASE STUDY ON THE AND VOCABULARY IN ROBERT BEEKES'S NEW ETYMOLOGICAL DICTIONARY OF GREEK |journal=Studia Linguistica Universitatis Iagellonicae Cracoviensis |date=2016 |volume=133 |issue=2 |doi=10.4467/20834624SL.16.006.5152}}</ref> The region has historically also been known as {{em|\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f (Makedonija)}} in [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] and the [[Slavic speakers of Greek Macedonia|local South Slavic dialects]], {{em|Makedonya}} in [[Turkish language|Turkish]], and {{em|Machedonia}} in [[Aromanian language|Aromanian or Vlach]].\n\n==History==\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n===Prehistory===\n{{details|Macedonia (region)#History}}\n\nMacedonia lies at the crossroads of human development between the Aegean and the Balkans. The earliest signs of human habitation date back to the [[palaeolithic]] period, notably with the [[Petralona cave]] in which was found the oldest yet known European humanoid, ''[[Archanthropus europaeus petraloniensis]]''. In the [[Late Neolithic]] period (c.&nbsp;4500 to 3500&nbsp;BC), trade took place with quite distant regions, indicating rapid socio-economic changes. One of the most important innovations was the start of copper working.\n\n===Ancient history===\n{{details|Macedonia (ancient kingdom)}}\n[[File:ExpansionOfMacedon.jpg|thumb|The expansion of the ancient Macedonian Kingdom up to the death of [[Philip II of Macedon|Phillip II]]]]\n[[File:Amfipoli, Greece - panoramio (3).jpg|thumb|200px|The [[Lion of Amphipolis]]; erected in 4th BC in honour of [[Laomedon of Mytilene]], general of Alexander the Great]]\n\nAccording to [[Herodotus]], the history of Macedonia began with the [[Ancient Macedonians|Makednoi]] tribe, among the first to use the name, migrating to the region from [[Histiaeotis]] in the south. There they lived near Thracian tribes such as the [[Bryges]] who would later leave Macedonia for [[Anatolia|Asia Minor]] and become known as [[Phrygia]]ns. ''[[Macedonia (terminology)#Etymology|Macedonia]]'' was named after the Makednoi. Accounts of other [[toponym]]s such as [[Imathia|Emathia]] are attested to have been in use before that. Herodotus claims that\na branch of the Macedonians invaded Southern Greece towards the end of the second millennium B.C. Upon reaching the Peloponnese the invaders were renamed [[Dorians]], triggering the accounts of the Dorian invasion. For centuries the Macedonian tribes were organized in independent kingdoms, in what is now Central Macedonia, and their role in internal Hellenic politics was minimal, even before the rise of Athens. The Macedonians claimed to be Dorian Greeks (Argive Greeks) and there were many [[Ionians]] in the coastal regions. The rest of the region was inhabited by various Thracian and Illyrian tribes as well as mostly coastal colonies of other Greek states such as [[Amphipolis]], Olynthos, Potidea, Stageira and many others, and to the north another tribe dwelt, called the [[Paeonians]]. During the late 6th and early 5th century BC, the region came under Persian rule until the destruction of Xerxes at [[Plataea]]. During the [[Peloponnesian War]], Macedonia became the theatre of many military actions by the [[Peloponnesian League]] and the Athenians, and saw incursions of Thracians and Illyrians, as attested by Thucydides. Many Macedonian cities were allied to the Spartans (both the Spartans and the Macedonians were Dorian, while the Athenians were Ionian), but Athens maintained the colony of Amphipolis under her control for many years. The kingdom of [[Macedon]], was reorganized by [[Philip II of Macedon|Philip II]] and achieved the union of Greek states by forming the [[League of Corinth]]. After his assassination, his son [[Alexander the Great|Alexander]] succeeded to the throne of Macedon and carrying the title of [[Hegemon]] of [[League of Corinth]] started his [[Wars of Alexander the Great|long campaign]] towards the east.\n\n===Roman period===\n{{See also|Macedonian Wars|Macedonia (Roman province)}}\n[[File:\u0391\u03a8\u0399\u0394\u0391 \u0393\u0391\u039b\u0395\u03a1\u0399\u039f\u03a5 2.jpg|thumb|View of the Roman-era [[Arch of Galerius and Rotunda|Arch of Galerius]] in Thessaloniki, capital of Roman Macedonia]]\n\nMacedonia remained an important and powerful kingdom until the [[Battle of Pydna]] (June 22, 168 BC), in which the Roman general [[Lucius Aemilius Paullus Macedonicus|Aemilius Paulus]] defeated King [[Perseus of Macedon]], ending the reign of the [[Antigonid dynasty]] over Macedonia. For a brief period a Macedonian republic called the \"Koinon of the Macedonians\" was established. It was divided into four administrative districts by the Romans in the hope that this would make revolts more difficult, but this manoeuvre failed. Then in 148 BC, Macedonia was fully annexed by the Romans.<ref name=\"Moutsopoulos\">N. K. Moutsopoulos, \u03a4\u03b1 \u0393\u03b5\u03c9\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u038c\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03a1\u03c9\u03bc\u03b1\u03ca\u03ba\u03ae \u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03b4\u03bf. \u039f\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03a4\u03b1\u03c7\u03c5\u03b4\u03c1\u03cc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2,  22 \u03a3\u03b5\u03c0\u03c4\u03b5\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 1994, \u03a3\u03b5\u03bb. 101.</ref> The northern boundary at that time ended at [[Lake Ohrid]] and [[Bylazora]], a Paeonian city near the modern city of [[Veles (city)|Veles]]. [[Strabo]], writing in the first century AD places the border of Macedonia on that part at [[Lychnidos]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0239:book=7:chapter=7&highlight=macedonia|title=Strabo, Geography, BOOK VII., CHAPTER VII.|publisher=}}</ref> Byzantine Achris and presently [[Ochrid]]. Therefore ancient Macedonia did not significantly extend beyond its current borders (in Greece). To the east, Macedonia ended according to [[Strabo]] at the river [[Struma (river)|Strymon]], although he mentions that other writers placed Macedonia's border with [[Thrace]] at the river [[Nestos (river)|Nestos]],<ref>{{cite book |first=D. C. |last=Samsaris |title=Historical Geography of Eastern Macedonia during Antiquity |language=el |location=Thessaloniki |year=1976 |pages=88\u201397 }}</ref> which is also the present geographical boundary between the two administrative districts of [[Greece]].\n\nThe [[Acts of the Apostles]] ({{bibleverse||Acts|16:9-10|NKJV}}) records a vision in which the [[Paul the Apostle|apostle Paul]] is said to have seen a '[[man of Macedonia]]' pleading with him, saying, \"Come over to Macedonia and help us\". The passage reports that Paul and his companions responded immediately to the invitation.\n\nSubsequently the provinces of [[Epirus (ancient state)|Epirus]] and [[Thessaly]] as well as other regions to the north were incorporated into a new Provincia Macedonia, but in 297 AD under a [[Diocletian]]ic reform many of these regions were removed and two new provinces were created: Macedonia Prima and Macedonia Salutaris (from 479 to 482 AD Macedonia Secunda). Macedonia Prima coincided approximately with Strabo's definition of Macedonia and with the modern administrative district of Greece<ref name=\"Moutsopoulos\" /> and had [[Thessalonica|Thessaloniki]] as its capital, while Macedonia Salutaris had the [[Paeonia (kingdom)|Paeonian]] city of [[Stobi]] (near [[Gradsko, North Macedonia|Gradsko]]) as its capital. This subdivision is mentioned in [[Hierocles of Alexandria|Hierocles]]' Synecdemon (527\u2013528) and remained through the reign of emperor [[Justinian]].\n\nThe [[Slav]]ic, [[Pannonian Avars|Avar]], [[First Bulgarian Empire|Bulgarian]] and [[Hungarian people|Magyar]] invasions in the 6\u20137th centuries devastated both provinces<ref>{{cite book |first=John Julius |last=Norwich |title=A short history of Byzantium |publisher=Penguin |year=1998 }}</ref> with only parts of Macedonia Prima in the coastal areas and nearer [[Western Thrace|Thrace]] remaining in [[Byzantine empire|Byzantine]] hands, while most of the hinterland was disputed between the [[Byzantine empire|Byzantium]] and [[First Bulgarian Empire|Bulgaria]]. The Macedonian regions under Byzantine control passed under the [[tourma]] of Macedonia to the province of [[Thrace]].\n\nA new system of administration came into place in 789\u2013802 AD, following the [[Byzantine empire]]'s recovery from these invasions. The new system was based on administrative divisions called [[Themata]]. The region of Macedonia Prima (the territory of modern Greek administrative district of Macedonia) was divided between the Thema of Thessaloniki and the Thema of Strymon, so that only the region of the area from [[Nestos (river)|Nestos]] eastwards continued to carry the name Macedonia, referred to as the [[Macedonia (theme)|Thema of Macedonia]] or the Thema of \"Macedonia in Thrace\". The Thema of Macedonia in Thrace had its capital in [[Adrianople]].<ref>\u0391\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u0394\u03b5\u03bb\u03b7\u03ba\u03ac\u03c1\u03b7, \u0393\u03b5\u03c9\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03c3\u03c4\u03af\u03b3\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03a1\u03c9\u03bc\u03b1\u03ca\u03ba\u03ae \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0392\u03c5\u03b6\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03ae \u0395\u03c0\u03bf\u03c7\u03ae, \"\u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03cc\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03c7\u03c1\u03cc\u03bd\u03bf\" \u03b5\u03ba\u03b4\u03cc\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Warren |last=Treadgold |title=Byzantium and Its Army 284\u20131081 |publisher=Stanford University Press |year=1995 |isbn=0-8047-2420-2 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=George |last=Ostrogorsky |title=History of the Byzantine State |publisher=Rutgers University Press |year=1986 |isbn=0-631-12782-8 }}</ref>\n\n===Medieval history===\n{{See also|Strymon (theme)|Thessalonica (theme)|Kingdom of Thessalonica|Empire of Thessalonica}}\n[[File:\u0386\u03c0\u03bf\u03c8\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03af\u03c7\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2, \u039a\u03ac\u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf \u039a\u03b1\u03b2\u03ac\u03bb\u03b1\u03c2 (photosiotas).jpg|thumb|View of the Byzantine fortress in the old town of [[Kavala]].]]\n[[File:GR-platamonas-festung.jpg|thumb|right|The Frankish [[Platamon Castle]].]]\n\nFamiliarity with the Slavic element in the area led two brothers from [[Thessaloniki]], [[Saints Cyril and Methodius]], to be chosen to convert the Slavs to [[Christianity]]. Following the campaigns of [[Basil II]], all of Macedonia returned to the Byzantine state. Following the [[Fourth Crusade]] 1203&ndash;1204, a short-lived [[Crusader states|Crusader]] realm, the [[Kingdom of Thessalonica]], was established in the region. It was subdued by the co-founder of the Greek [[Despotate of Epirus]], [[Theodore Komnenos Doukas]] in 1224, when Greek Macedonia and the city of [[Thessaloniki]] were at the heart of the short-lived [[Empire of Thessalonica]]. Returning to the restored [[Byzantine Empire]] shortly thereafter, Greek Macedonia remained in Byzantine hands until the 1340s, when all of Macedonia (except Thessaloniki, and possibly [[Veria]]) was conquered by the Serbian ruler [[Stephen Uro\u0161 IV Du\u0161an of Serbia|Stefan Du\u0161an]].<ref>Fine, ''The Late Medieval Balkans'', 301&ndash;302</ref> Divided between Serbia and [[Second Bulgarian Empire|Bulgaria]] after Du\u0161an's death, the region fell quickly to the advancing [[Ottoman Empire|Ottomans]], with Thessaloniki alone holding out until 1387. After a brief Byzantine interval in 1403&ndash;1430 (during the last seven years of which the city was handed over to the Venetians), Thessaloniki and its immediate surrounding area returned to the Ottomans.<ref>Vacalopoulos, ''History of Macedonia 1354&ndash;1833'', [http://www.promacedonia.org/en/av/av_3_4.htm 89&ndash;97]</ref>\n\n===Ottoman rule===\n{{Main|Ottoman Greece|Salonica Eyalet|Salonica Vilayet}}\n[[File:KRITOPOULOS 1627.JPG|thumb|160px|[[Metrophanes Kritopoulos]], theologian, monk and [[List of Greek Orthodox Patriarchs of Alexandria|Patriarch of Alexandria]] who was born in [[Veria]] in 1589.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/378855/Metrophanes-Kritopoulos|title= Metrophanes Kritopoulos.|publisher= www.britannica.com |accessdate=2009-08-31|quote= Metrophanes Kritopoulos Greek patriarch and theologian - born 1589, Beroea, Macedonia, [[Ottoman Empire]] died May 30, 1639, Walachia}}</ref>]]\n\nThe capture of [[Thessalonica|Thessaloniki]] in 1430 threw the Byzantine world into consternation, being regarded correctly as a prelude to the fall of [[Constantinople]] itself. The memory of the event has survived through folk traditions containing fact and myths. Apostolos Vacalopoulos records the following Turkish tradition connected with the capture of Thessaloniki:<ref>Vacalopoulos, ''History of Macedonia 1354&ndash;1833'', [http://www.promacedonia.org/en/av/av_3_4.htm 97]</ref>\n{{quote|\"While [[Murad II|Murad]] was asleep in his palace at Yenitsa, the story has it that, God appeared to him in a dream and gave him a lovely rose to smell, full of perfume. The sultan was so amazed by its beauty that he begged God to give it to him. God replied, \"This rose, Murad, is Thessalonica. Know that it is to you granted by heaven to enjoy it. Do not waste time; go and take it\". Complying with this exhortation from, Murad marched against Thessalonica and, as it has been written, captured it.\"}}\n\n[[Thessaloniki]] became a centre of [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] administration in the Balkans. While most of Macedonia was ruled by the Ottomans, in [[Mount Athos]] the monastic community continued to exist in a state of autonomy. The remainder of the [[Chalkidiki]] peninsula also enjoyed an autonomous status: the \"Koinon of Mademochoria\" was governed by a locally appointed council due to privileges obtained on account of its wealth, coming from the gold and silver mines in the area.\n\nThere were several uprisings in Macedonia during [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman rule]], including an uprising after the [[Battle of Lepanto]] that ended in massacres of the Greek population, the uprising in [[Naousa, Imathia|Naousa]] of the armatolos [[Zisis Karademos]] in 1705, a rebellion in the area of [[Grevena]] by a [[Klepht]] called Ziakas (1730\u20131810) and the Greek Declaration of Independence in Macedonia by [[Emmanouel Pappas|Emmanuel Pappas]] in 1821, during the [[Greek War of Independence]]. In 1854 [[Theodoros Ziakas]], the son of the klepht Ziakas, together with [[Dimitrios Karatasos]], who had been among  the captains at the siege of [[Naousa, Imathia|Naousa]] in 1821, led another uprising in Western Macedonia that has been profusely commemorated in Greek folk song.\n\n===Modern history===\n{{Main|Greek War of Independence|Greek Struggle for Macedonia|Balkan Wars|Macedonian Front|Movement of National Defence}}\n[[File:1st Battalion of the National Defence army marches for the front.jpeg|thumb|right|200px|The 1st Battalion of the [[Provisional Government of National Defence|National Defence]] marches on its way to the Front, during WWI.]]\n\nGreece gained the southern parts of the region with Thessaloniki from the [[Ottoman Empire]] after the [[First Balkan War]], and expanded its share in the [[Second Balkan War]] against Bulgaria. The boundaries of Greek Macedonia were finalized in the [[Treaty of Bucharest (1913)|Treaty of Bucharest]]. In [[World War I]], Macedonia became a battlefield. The Greek Prime Minister, [[Eleftherios Venizelos]], favoured entering the war on the side of the [[Allies of World War I|Entente]], while the Germanophile King [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine I]] favored neutrality. Invited by Venizelos, in autumn 1915, the Allies landed forces in Thessaloniki to aid [[Serbia]] in [[Serbian Campaign (World War I)|its war]] against Austria-Hungary and Bulgaria, but their intervention came too late to prevent the Serbian collapse. The [[Macedonian front]] was established, with Thessaloniki at its heart, while in summer 1916 the Bulgarians [[Struma operation|took over]] Greek eastern Macedonia without opposition. This provoked a military uprising among pro-Venizelist officers in Thessaloniki, resulting in the establishment of a \"[[Provisional Government of National Defence]]\" in the city, headed by Venizelos, which entered the war alongside the Allies. After intense diplomatic negotiations and an [[Noemvriana|armed confrontation]] in Athens between Entente and royalist forces the King abdicated, and his second son [[Alexander of Greece|Alexander]] took his place. Venizelos returned to Athens in June 1917 and Greece, now unified, officially joined the war on the side of the Allies.\n\nIn [[World War II]] Macedonia was [[Axis occupation of Greece|occupied by the Axis]] (1941\u201344), with Germany taking western and central Macedonia with Thessaloniki and Bulgaria occupying and annexing eastern Macedonia.\n\nAt the beginning of the 19th century, Slavic peasants identified themselves based on belonging to their family, village, or local region, or as \"[[Rum Millet]]\", i.e. members of the Greek-dominated community of Orthodox Christians. The Slavs of Macedonia generally referred to themselves and were known as \"Bulgarians\", but the word \"Bulgarian\" invoked the idea of a poor, Slav-speaking peasant.  By the middle of the 19th century, peasant communities of Macedonia experienced the formation of deep divisions with [[rise of nationalism in the Ottoman Empire]]. From then, the [[Slavic speakers in Ottoman Macedonia|Slavic speaking communities of northern Greece]] split into two hostile and opposed groups with two different national identities - Greek and Bulgarian.<ref>Gounaris, Basil G. (1995). \"Social Cleavages and National \"Awakening\" in Ottoman Macedonia\". East European Quarterly. 29 (4): 409\u2013426.</ref> By the Second World War and following the defeat of Bulgaria, another further split between the Slavic groups occurred. Conservatives departed with the occupying Bulgarian Army to Bulgaria. Leftists who identified as Macedonians (Slavic), joined the communist-dominated rebel [[Democratic Army of Greece]]. At the conclusion of the [[Greek Civil War]] (1946\u201349), most Macedonians of Slavic background were evacuated by the [[Greek Communist Party]] and forced to flee to the [[Socialist Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] [[Socialist Republic of Macedonia]] and other countries in Eastern and Central Europe.<ref>cite web|https://www.balcanicaucaso.org/eng/Areas/North-Macedonia/Macedonian-Refugee-Children-Exodus-Anniversary-42415|cite-title=Macedonian Refugee Children: Exodus Anniversary|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/2019*/https://www.balcanicaucaso.org/eng/Areas/North-Macedonia/Macedonian-Refugee-Children-Exodus-Anniversary-42415</ref> Some also immigrated to [[Canada]], [[Australia]], and the [[United States]].<ref>Panayiotis Diamadis et al. (1995) A Child's Grief. A Nation's Lament Sydney: Stentor Press.</ref> Current Greek law still forbids the reentry and restitution of property by Macedonians that are not \"Greek by origin.\"<ref>cite web|https://www.balcanicaucaso.org/eng/Areas/North-Macedonia/Macedonian-Refugee-Children-Exodus-Anniversary-42415|cite-title=Macedonian Refugee Children: Exodus Anniversary|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/2019*/https://www.balcanicaucaso.org/eng/Areas/North-Macedonia/Macedonian-Refugee-Children-Exodus-Anniversary-42415</ref>\n\n== Regions and local government ==\n[[file:Topographic map of Macedonia (Greece).svg|thumb|300px|Topographic map of Macedonia]]\n[[file:Macedonia (Greece) map of K\u00f6ppen climate classification.svg|thumb|300px|[[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] map of Macedonia]]\n\nSince 1987 Macedonia has been divided into three [[modern regions of Greece|regions]] ({{lang-el|\u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c6\u03ad\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b5\u03c2}}). These are [[Western Macedonia]], [[Central Macedonia]], and Eastern Macedonia, which is part of the region of [[Eastern Macedonia and Thrace]]. These regions are further subdivided into fourteen [[regional units of Greece|regional units]] ({{Lang|el|\u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c6\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03b5\u03bd\u03cc\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2}}), which are in turn divided into [[Communities and Municipalities of Greece|municipalities]] ({{Lang|el|\u03b4\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf\u03b9}}) or communities ({{Lang|el|\u03ba\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03cc\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2}} &ndash; roughly equivalent to [[United Kingdom|British]] or [[Australian]] [[shire]]s). They are overseen by the [[Minister for the Interior and Public Order (Greece)|Ministry for the Interior]], while the [[Deputy Minister for Macedonia and Thrace]] is responsible for the coordination and application of the government's policies in all three Macedonian regions.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Role of the Ministry |language=Greek |publisher=Greek Ministry of Macedonia and Thrace |url=http://www.mathra.gr/default_15.aspx |accessdate=2009-05-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090513004551/http://www.mathra.gr/default_15.aspx |archivedate=2009-05-13 }}</ref> Prior to 1987 Macedonia was a single administrative and geographical unit.\n\nThe heads of the various administrative units are elected. The last Greek local elections [[2014 Greek local elections|were in 2014]], and saw [[Apostolos Tzitzikostas]] elected regional governor of [[Central Macedonia]], [[Giorgos Pavlidis]] in [[Eastern Macedonia and Thrace]], and [[Theodoros Karypidis]] in Western Macedonia. Tzitzikostas and Pavlidis are members of the [[centre-right politics|centre-right]] [[New Democracy (Greece)|New Democracy]] party, while Karypidis is an [[independent politician|independent]]. Elections take place in a [[two-round system]], where the two candidates with the most votes face each other in a second round if no one has managed to get a [[majority]] of more than 50% of the votes in the first round. Regional councils, mayors, and other officials are also elected in this way. The next local elections will take place in 2019. The [[Deputy Minister for Macedonia and Thrace]] is not an elected position, and is instead appointed at the pleasure of the [[Prime Minister of Greece]]. The current Deputy Minister in the [[Cabinet of Kyriakos Mitsotakis]] is {{interlanguage link|Theodoros Karaoglou|el|\u0398\u03b5\u03cc\u03b4\u03c9\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03b1\u03c1\u03ac\u03bf\u03b3\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5}} of [[New Democracy (Greece)|New Democracy]]. The various [[regions of Greece]] are also constituencies to the [[Hellenic Parliament]], and Macedonia is represented through its 66 [[Member of Parliament|Members of Parliament]].<ref name=\"mps\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hellenicparliament.gr/UserFiles/f3c70a23-7696-49db-9148-f24dce6a27c8/katalogos-elkoges9%2015.pdf |script-title=el:\u039f\u039d\u039f\u039c\u0391\u03a3\u03a4\u0399\u039a\u039f\u03a3 \u039a\u0391\u03a4\u0391\u039b\u039f\u0393\u039f\u03a3 \u0392\u039f\u03a5\u039b\u0395\u03a5\u03a4\u03a9\u039d (\u039a\u0391\u03a4\u0391 \u03a0\u0395\u03a1\u0399\u03a6\u0395\u03a1\u0395\u0399\u0395\u03a3) |date=25 May 2015 |publisher=[[Hellenic Parliament]] |location=Athens |language=Greek |trans-title=List of Names of Members of Parliament (by constituency). |access-date=12 February 2019}}</ref> Thessaloniki is split into two constituencies, [[Thessaloniki A (Hellenic Parliament constituency)|Thessaloniki A]] and [[Thessaloniki B (Hellenic Parliament constituency)|Thessaloniki B]], while [[Grevena]] is the smallest constituency with only 1 seat.<ref name=\"mps\" /> Thessaloniki A is the second-largest constituency in Greece with 16 MPs.<ref name=\"mps\" />\n\nMacedonia is bordered by the neighboring Greek regions of [[Thessaly]] to the south, [[Western Thrace|Thrace]] (part of [[Eastern Macedonia and Thrace]]) to the east, and [[Epirus (region)|Epirus]] to the west. It also includes the [[Autonomous administrative division|autonomous]] [[monasticism|monastic]] state of [[Mount Athos]], which has existed as a religious sanctuary since the [[Middle Ages]]. Mount Athos is under the spiritual jurisdiction of the [[Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople]] and is inaccessible to women, punishable by a penalty of [[incarceration]] of up to twelve months.<ref name=\"europarl athos\">{{cite news|date=5 September 2003|title=European Parliament Adopts Report on Fundamental Rights in the EU &ndash; Mt Athos Status|publisher=Embassy of Greece in the US|url=http://www.greekembassy.org/embassy/Content/en/Article.aspx?office=3&folder=360&article=11935&hilite=rehabilitation|accessdate=2009-05-08|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512194018/http://www.greekembassy.org/embassy/Content/en/Article.aspx?office=3&folder=360&article=11935&hilite=rehabilitation|archivedate=12 May 2012}}</ref> This has been criticized by the [[European Parliament]].<ref name=\"europarl athos\" /> The territory of Mount Athos is a self-governing part of Greece, and the powers of the state are exercised through a governor  appointed by the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Greece)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]]. The [[European Union]] takes this special status into consideration, particularly on matters of taxation exemption and rights of installation.<ref>Council of Europe, ''Structure and Operation of Local and Regional Democracy'', 8. See also the article 105 of the [[Constitution of Greece]] and the Common Declaration on Mount Athos attached to the Treaty of Entry of Greece  to the EEC (1 January 1981).</ref> Macedonia borders the sovereign states of [[Albania]] to the north-west, [[North Macedonia]] to the north, and [[Bulgaria]] to the north-east. The table below is a concise list of the various subdivisions of Macedonia:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|- style=\"font-size:100%; text-align:left\"\n! style=\"width:40px;\"| Map of Macedonia !!colspan=\"2\"| Subdivisions {{As of|2011|lc=y}} !! \"| [[Capital (political)|Capital]] !! [[Area]] !! [[Population]]<ref name=\"census 2011\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=20 | [[File:Greek Macedonia map with subdivisions.svg|350px]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffcbcb;\" rowspan=\"5\"| || '''[[West Macedonia|West&nbsp;Macedonia]]''' || '''[[Kozani]]''' ||style=\"text-align:right\" |'''9,451 km<sup>2</sup>'''||style=\"text-align:right\" |'''283,689'''\n|-\n|1. [[Kastoria (regional unit)|Kastoria]] || [[Kastoria]] || style=\"text-align:right\" |1,720 km<sup>2</sup>|| style=\"text-align:right\" |50,322\n|-\n|2. [[Florina (regional unit)|Florina]] || [[Florina]] || style=\"text-align:right\" |1,924 km<sup>2</sup>|| style=\"text-align:right\" |51,414\n|-\n|3. [[Kozani (regional unit)|Kozani]] || [[Kozani]] ||style=\"text-align:right\" |3,516 km<sup>2</sup>|| style=\"text-align:right\" |150,196\n|-\n|4. [[Grevena (regional unit)|Grevena]] || [[Grevena]] || style=\"text-align:right\" |2,291 km<sup>2</sup>|| style=\"text-align:right\" |31,757\n|-\n| style=\"background:#b9ffc5;\" rowspan=\"8\"| || '''[[Central Macedonia|Central&nbsp;Macedonia]]''' || '''[[Thessaloniki]]''' ||style=\"text-align:right\" |'''18,811 km<sup>2</sup>'''||style=\"text-align:right\" |'''1,882,108'''\n|-\n|5. [[Pella (regional unit)|Pella]] || [[Edessa, Greece|Edessa]] || style=\"text-align:right\"|2,506 km<sup>2</sup>|| style=\"text-align:right\"|139,680\n|-\n|6. [[Imathia]] || [[Veria]] ||style=\"text-align:right\"|1,701&nbsp;km\u00b2|| style=\"text-align:right\"|140,611\n|-\n|7. [[Pieria (regional unit)|Pieria]] || [[Katerini]] || style=\"text-align:right\"|1,516 km<sup>2</sup>|| style=\"text-align:right\"|126,698\n|-\n|8. [[Kilkis (regional unit)|Kilkis]] || [[Kilkis]] || style=\"text-align:right\"|2,519 km<sup>2</sup>|| style=\"text-align:right\"|80,419\n|-\n|9. [[Thessaloniki (regional unit)|Thessaloniki]] || [[Thessaloniki]] || style=\"text-align:right\"|3,683 km<sup>2</sup>|| style=\"text-align:right\"|1,110,551\n|-\n|10. [[Chalkidiki]] || [[Polygyros]] || style=\"text-align:right\"|2,918&nbsp;km\u00b2|| style=\"text-align:right\"|105,908\n|-\n|11. [[Serres (regional unit)|Serres]] || [[Serres]] || style=\"text-align:right\"|3.968 km<sup>2</sup>|| style=\"text-align:right\"|176,430\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ccf;\" rowspan=\"4\"| || '''[[East Macedonia and Thrace|East&nbsp;Macedonia]]'''<br>{{nowrap|(<small>Part of [[East Macedonia and Thrace]]</small>)}} ||'''[[Kavala]]''' ||style=\"text-align:right\"|'''5,579 km<sup>2</sup>'''||style=\"text-align:right\"|'''238,785'''\n|-\n|12. [[Drama (regional unit)|Drama]] || [[Drama, Greece|Drama]] || style=\"text-align:right\"|3,468 km<sup>2</sup>|| style=\"text-align:right\"|98,287\n|-\n|13. [[Kavala (regional unit)|Kavala]] || [[Kavala]] || style=\"text-align:right\"|1,728 km<sup>2</sup>|| style=\"text-align:right\"|124,917\n|-\n|14. [[Thasos]] || [[Thasos town|Thasos]] || style=\"text-align:right\"|379 km<sup>2</sup>|| style=\"text-align:right\"|13,770\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffeeaa;\">| || 15. [[Mount Athos]] (autonomous) || [[Karyes (Athos)|Karyes]] || style=\"text-align:right\"|336 km<sup>2</sup>|| style=\"text-align:right\"|1,811\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Macedonia (total) !!style=\"text-align:left\"| [[Thessaloniki]] !!style=\"text-align:right\"|34,177 km<sup>2</sup> !!style=\"text-align:right\"|2,406,393\n|}\n\n==Economy and transport==\n[[File:Port of Thessaloniki.png|thumb|The [[Port of Thessaloniki|port]] of [[Thessaloniki]], the major economic and industrial center]]\n[[File:Egnatia Odos.JPG|thumb|View of the [[Egnatia Odos (modern road)|Egnatia odos]] highway]]\n{{See also|Economy of Greece|Transport in Greece}}\n\nThe [[Gross Domestic Product]] of Macedonia peaked at \u20ac41.99 billion (${{toUSD|41.99|EUR|2017}} billion) in nominal value and \u20ac46.87 billion (${{toUSD|46.87|EUR|2017}} billion) in [[purchasing power parity]] just before the [[Great Recession]] in 2008;<ref name=\"Eurostat GDP\" /> it has since then contracted to its lowest point in 2015, during the [[Greek government-debt crisis]], to \u20ac30.85 billion (${{toUSD|30.85|EUR|2017}} billion) and \u20ac38.17 billion (${{toUSD|38.17|EUR|2017}} billion);<ref name=\"Eurostat GDP\" /> a decrease of 26.5%. Greece exited its recession, which began in 2009, in 2016 but data from that year onward is not available for the whole of Macedonia; [[Central Macedonia]] grew by 0.57% in real terms that year to \u20ac23.85 billion (${{toUSD|23.85|EUR|2017}} billion), while [[Western Macedonia]] contracted by 10.6% to \u20ac3.85 billion (${{toUSD|3.85|EUR|2017}} billion).<ref name=\"Eurostat GDP\" /> Almost half of the economy, 49%, is centered in the [[Thessaloniki (regional unit)|Thessaloniki regional unit]],<ref name=\"Eurostat GDP\" /> which remained in a recession in 2015, declining by 0.4%.<ref name=\"Eurostat GDP\" />\n\nThe recession had an impact on the [[per capita income]] of the region, especially when compared with the [[European Union]] average. Western Macedonia, the region with the highest per capita income, saw it drop from 83% the EU average in 2008 to 59% in 2016.<ref name=\"Eurostat GDP\" /> The per capita income of Macedonia in 2015 was \u20ac12,900 in nominal and \u20ac15,900 in purchasing power terms.<ref name=\"Eurostat GDP\" /><ref name=\"Pops for GDP\">{{cite web |url=http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/show.do?dataset=nama_10r_3popgdp&lang=en |title=Average annual population to calculate regional GDP data (thousand persons) by NUTS 3 regions |publisher=[[Eurostat]] |accessdate=8 February 2019 }}</ref> The Macedonian economy is primarily [[Tertiary sector of the economy|service-based]], with services contributing \u20ac16.46 billion (60.4%) of the region's [[gross value added]] in 2015.<ref name=\"gross value added\">{{cite web |url=http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/show.do?dataset=nama_10r_3gva&lang=en |title=Gross value added at basic prices by NUTS 3 regions |publisher=[[Eurostat]] |accessdate=8 February 2019 }}</ref> The [[Secondary sector of the economy|industrial]] and [[primary sector of the economy|agricultural]] sectors contributed \u20ac9.06 billion (33.3%) and \u20ac1.72 billion  (6.3%) respectively.<ref name=\"gross value added\" /> The regional labour force was similarly mostly employed in services (60.4%), with industry and agriculture making up 25.6% and 14.0% of the labour force.<ref name=\"employment\">{{cite web |url=http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/show.do?dataset=nama_10r_3empers&lang=en |title=Employment (thousand persons) by NUTS 3 regions |publisher=[[Eurostat]] |accessdate=9 February 2019 }}</ref>\n\nMacedonia is home to Greece's richest farmland,<ref name=\"Britannica\" /> and the region accounts for {{convert|9,859|sqkm|sqmi}} of the country's agricultural area (30% of total).<ref name=\"agric area 2009\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gr/el/statistics?p_p_id=documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ&p_p_lifecycle=2&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_cacheability=cacheLevelPage&p_p_col_id=column-2&p_p_col_count=4&p_p_col_pos=2&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_javax.faces.resource=document&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_ln=downloadResources&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_documentID=245232&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_locale=el |title=\u0395\u03ba\u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u03b5\u03cd\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c7\u03c1\u03b7\u03c3\u03b9\u03bc\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u03bf\u03cd\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03b7 \u03b3\u03b5\u03c9\u03c1\u03b3\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03ad\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7, \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c6\u03ad\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03cc |trans-title=Uses and cultivated agricultural area, by region and prefecture |publisher=[[Hellenic Statistical Authority]] |website=www.statistics.gr |year=2009 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> Macedonia's agricultural production has historically been dominated by [[tobacco]], with the [[cash crop]] being grown in large quantities due to its value. Central and Western Macedonia still produce 41% of Greece's total tobacco, but it only represents 1.4% of these regions' agricultural production value.<ref name=\"agric production 2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gr/el/statistics?p_p_id=documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ&p_p_lifecycle=2&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_cacheability=cacheLevelPage&p_p_col_id=column-2&p_p_col_count=4&p_p_col_pos=2&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_javax.faces.resource=document&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_ln=downloadResources&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_documentID=343138&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_locale=el |title=\u039f\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03af \u039b\u03bf\u03b3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03af \u0393\u03b5\u03c9\u03c1\u03b3\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03b3\u03b5\u03c9\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03b6\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c6\u03ad\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 (\u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c9\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03ac \u03a3\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9\u03c7\u03b5\u03af\u03b1) |trans-title=Financial Accounts of Agriculture by geographic zone and region (Temporary Data) |publisher=[[Hellenic Statistical Authority]] |website=www.statistics.gr |year=2016 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> Nowadays the regional agricultural economy is centered around [[cereal]], [[fruit]], and [[industrial crop]]s. Overall Central and Western Macedonia account for 25% of the value of Greek agricultural produce (including 41% of fruit and 43% cereal).<ref name=\"agric production 2016\" /> A brand identity for products made in Macedonia, called \"Macedonia the GReat\", was launched in 2019 by the Greek government.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/246487/gallery/ekathimerini/in-images/greece-unveils-macedonia-trademark |title=Greece unveils Macedonia trademark |work=[[Kathimerini]] |access-date=2019-11-17 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nThe [[European Union]] considers most of Macedonia to be a less developed region of the Union for its 2014{{endash}}2020 funding cycle,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ec.europa.eu/regional_policy/sources/images/map/eligible2014/gr.pdf |title=Structural Funds (ERDF and ESF) eligibility 2014{{endash}}2020 |website=www.ec.europa.eu |publisher=[[European Commission]] |access-date=2019-02-09}}</ref> and so the region has in recent years benefited from a number of [[megaproject]]s co-financed by the [[Government of Greece|Greek government]] and the EU. These included the [[Egnatia Odos (modern road)|Egnatia Odos]] [[Controlled-access highway|freeway]] (\u20ac5.93 billion)<ref name=\"Egnatia\">{{cite web |author=Egnatia Odos |url=http://www.egnatia.eu/page/default.asp?la=2&id=3460 |title=The Construction of the Egnatia Motorway |website=www.egnatia.eu |accessdate=18 August 2018}}</ref> and the [[Thessaloniki Metro]] (\u20ac1.85 billion)<ref name=\"Financial Statement 2017\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ametro.gr/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/AM_Xrimatooikonomikes_katastaseis_2017.pdf |script-title=el:\u03a7\u03c1\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03bf\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u039a\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7 \u03c7\u03c1\u03ae\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ad\u03bb\u03b7\u03be\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd 31 \u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03b5\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 2017  |date=31 December 2017 |website=www.ametro.gr |publisher=Attiko Metro |page=9 |language=Greek |trans-title=Annual Financial Statements for the Year Ending on 31 December 2017}}</ref> while the railway network has also been partly electrified, allowing [[Thessaloniki]] to be linked with [[Athens]] in 3.5 hours through a [[high-speed rail|high speed railway]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/232431/article/ekathimerini/news/silver-arrow-high-speed-train-makes-test-run-in-thessaloniki |title='Silver Arrow' high-speed train makes test run in Thessaloniki |website=www.ekathimerini.com |publisher=[[Kathimerini]] |language=English |access-date=2019-02-09}}</ref> The [[Proastiakos Thessaloniki|Thessaloniki Suburban Railway]] links the regional capital with [[Florina]], in Western Macedonia, and [[Larissa]], in [[Thessaly]]. [[Thessaloniki Airport]] is the third-busiest in the country,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ypa.gr/userfiles/4659ed30-b59b-4111-9747-a3550129731a/%CE%A3%CE%A4%CE%91%CE%A4%CE%99%CE%A3%CE%A4%CE%99%CE%9A%CE%97%20%CE%91%CE%95%CE%A1%CE%9F%CE%A0%CE%9F%CE%A1%CE%99%CE%9A%CE%97%CE%A3%20%CE%9A%CE%99%CE%9D%CE%97%CE%A3%CE%97%CE%A3%202017_1.pdf |title=Air Traffic Statistics |website=www.ypa.gr |publisher=[[Hellenic Civil Aviation Authority]] |access-date=2019-02-09}}</ref> and the Athens{{endash}}Thessaloniki air route was the EU's tenth busiest in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/show.do?dataset=avia_par_el&lang=en |title=International intra-EU air passenger transport by reporting country and EU partner country |date=2016 |website=www.eurostat.ec.europa.eu |publisher=[[Eurostat]] |access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref> Macedonia's three other airports are [[Kavala International Airport|Kavala Airport]], [[Kozani National Airport|Kozani Airport]], and [[Kastoria National Airport|Kastoria Airport]]; the two busiest airports, Thessaloniki and Kavala, are operated by [[Fraport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fraport-greece.com/ell/profil-aerodromion |title=\u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c6\u03af\u03bb \u0391\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03b4\u03c1\u03bf\u03bc\u03af\u03c9\u03bd |website=www.fraport-greece.com |publisher=Fraport Greece |access-date=2019-02-09}}</ref> The [[Port of Thessaloniki]] is Greece's second-largest in domestic freight and fourth-largest in international freight by tonnage,<ref name=\"ports domestic 2018\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gr/el/statistics?p_p_id=documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ&p_p_lifecycle=2&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_cacheability=cacheLevelPage&p_p_col_id=column-2&p_p_col_count=4&p_p_col_pos=2&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_javax.faces.resource=document&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_ln=downloadResources&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_documentID=347357&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_locale=el |title=\u0395\u03ba\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03c9\u03b8\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03c9\u03b8\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1 \u03b5\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03b5\u03cd\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 \u03bb\u03b9\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2, \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03bb\u03b9\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03b7\u03b3\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1 \u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 |trans-title=Unloaded and loaded goods in Greek ports, by ports and type of cargo (2nd Quarter 2018) |publisher=[[Hellenic Statistical Authority]] |website=www.statistics.gr |year=2018 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref><ref name=\"ports international 2018\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gr/el/statistics?p_p_id=documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ&p_p_lifecycle=2&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_cacheability=cacheLevelPage&p_p_col_id=column-2&p_p_col_count=4&p_p_col_pos=2&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_javax.faces.resource=document&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_ln=downloadResources&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_documentID=347358&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_locale=el |title=\u0395\u03ba\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03c9\u03b8\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03c9\u03b8\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1 \u03b5\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03b5\u03cd\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u03b5\u03be\u03c9\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 \u03bb\u03b9\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03bb\u03b9\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03b7\u03b3\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1 \u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 |trans-title=Unloaded and loaded goods from abroad in Greek ports by ports and type of cargo (2nd Quarter 2018) |publisher=[[Hellenic Statistical Authority]] |website=www.statistics.gr |year=2018 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> while [[Kavala]] is Macedonia's other major port.\n\nMacedonia, being a border region of an EU member state, benefits from EU programs promoting cross-border economic collaboration both between members of the Union ([[Bulgaria]]),<ref name=\"keep bulgaria\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.keep.eu/programme/2014-2020-interreg-v-a-greece-bulgaria |title=2014 - 2020 INTERREG V-A Greece - Bulgaria |website=www.keep.eu |access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> as well as the [[North Macedonia|Republic of North Macedonia]],<ref name=\"keep fyrom\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.keep.eu/programme/2014-2020-interreg-ipa-cbc-greece-former-yugoslav-republic-of-macedonia |title=2014 - 2020 Interreg IPA CBC Greece - Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia |website=www.keep.eu |access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> an EU candidate country, and [[Albania]].<ref name=\"keep albania\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.keep.eu/programme/2014-2020-interreg-ipa-cbc-greece-albania |title=2014 - 2020 Interreg IPA CBC Greece - Albania |website=www.keep.eu |access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> The EU invested \u20ac210 million (${{toUSD|210|EUR|2017}} million) in these three programs for the 2014{{endash}}2020 funding cycle.<ref name=\"keep bulgaria\" /><ref name=\"keep fyrom\" /><ref name=\"keep albania\" /> A \u20ac10 billion (${{toUSD|10|EUR|2017}} billion) [[Egnatia Railway]] crossing Macedonia and linking [[Alexandroupoli]] in [[Western Thrace]] with [[Igoumenitsa]] in [[Epirus (region)|Epirus]] was proposed to the [[European Commission]] in 2017 but remains in planning with a projected start date in 2019.<ref name=\"egnatia railway\">{{Cite web |url=https://ec.europa.eu/eipp/desktop/en/projects/project-64.html |title=Egnatia Railway |website=ec.europa.eu |access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> If completed, the {{convert|565|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"egnatia railway\" /> railway line will be Europe's largest rail [[megaproject]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/sponsored/greece-infrastructure/ |title=Greece Infrastructure |magazine=Foreign Policy |language=en |access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref>\n\n==Tourism==\n{{see also|Tourism in Greece}}\n\n[[file:Halkidiki,DSC 1052.jpg|thumb|200px|A beach in [[Chalkidiki]]]]\n[[File:File0028_Aliakmonas.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Haliacmon]], the longest river in Greece]]\n\nCentral Macedonia is the most popular tourist destination in Greece that is not an island, and its fourth overall, outperforming all other regions of the [[Greek mainland]] with 9.7 million overnight stays in 2017.<ref name=\"Fig 2018\" /> There were a further 2.1 million stays in [[Eastern Macedonia and Thrace]] and 294 thousand in [[Western Macedonia]].<ref name=\"Fig 2018\" />\n\nMacedonia is a diverse region which allows it to cater to a variety of different types of tourism.<ref name=\"discover greece\">{{cite web |url=https://www.discovergreece.com:443/en/mainland/macedonia |title=Macedonia: a region of a thousand landscapes |website=[[Discover Greece]] |language=en |access-date=2019-02-09}}</ref> The [[Chalkidiki]] peninsula is Macedonia's most popular beach destination, combining {{convert|550|km|mi}} of sandy beaches with dense forests.<ref name=\"discover greece\" /> There were 116 [[Blue Flag beach]]es in Macedonia in 2018, 85 of which were in Chalkidiki.<ref name=\"blue flags\">{{cite web |url=https://eepf.gr/el/blueflag-2018-awards |title=\u0393\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03b6\u03b9\u03b5\u03c2 \u03a3\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1\u03af\u03b5\u03c2 2018 |website=www.eepf.gr |trans-title=Blue Flags 2018 |access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref> Additionally, the region was home to three Blue Flag marinas and one sustainable boating tourism operator.<ref name=\"blue flags\" /> Chalkidiki is also home to [[Mount Athos]], which is an important centre of [[religious tourism]]. The mountainous interior allows for [[hiking]] activities and [[adventure sports]],<ref name=\"lonely planet\">{{cite web |url=https://www.lonelyplanet.com/greece/macedonia |title=Macedonia travel {{endash}} Greece |website=www.lonelyplanet.com |publisher=[[Lonely Planet]] |language=en |access-date=2019-02-09}}</ref> while [[ski resort]]s like [[Vasilitsa]] also operate in the winter months.<ref name=\"visit greece\">{{cite web |url=http://www.visitgreece.gr/en/destinations/explore_macedonia |title=Explore Macedonia |website=www.visitgreece.gr |publisher=[[Greek National Tourism Organization|Visit Greece]] |access-date=2019-02-09}}</ref> Macedonia is home to four of [[List of World Heritage Sites in Greece|Greece's 18 UNESCO World Heritage sites]] (including [[Vergina|Aigai]], one of the capitals of [[Macedonia (ancient kingdom)|ancient Macedonia]]), and these are important poles for [[cultural tourism]].<ref name=\"lonely planet\" /> Apart from being the cultural centre of Macedonia, [[Thessaloniki]] is also a hub for urban tourism and [[gastronomy]].<ref name=\"lonely planet\" /> Macedonia is also home to various [[lake]] and [[wetland]] tourist destinations.<ref name=\"visit greece\" />\n\n==Culture==\n{{Main|Culture of Greece}}\n{{See also|List of Greeks|List of Macedonians (Greek)}}\n\n===Religion===\n[[File:Solu\u0148, chr\u00e1m u muzea Makedonsk\u00e9ho utrpen\u00ed.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Saint Gregory Palamas Metropolitan Cathedral in [[Thessaloniki]]]]\n{{Main|Religion in Greece}}\nThe main religion in the Greek region of Macedonia is [[Christianity]], with majority of population belonging to the [[Eastern Orthodox Church]]. In early centuries of Christianity, the see of [[Thessaloniki]] became the [[metropolitan diocese]] of the ancient Roman province of [[Macedonia (Roman province)|Macedonia]]. The [[Metropolis of Thessaloniki|archbishop of Thessaloniki]] also became the senior ecclesiastical primate of the entire [[Eastern Illyricum]], and in 535 his jurisdiction was reduced to the administrative territory of the [[Diocese of Macedonia]]. In the 8th century, from [[Holy See|Rome]] it came under the jurisdiction of the [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople]], and remained the main ecclesiastical center in the historical region of Macedonia throughout the Middle Ages, and up to the modern times.{{sfn|Nesbitt|Oikonomides|1991|p=51}}\n\n===Macedonian cuisine===\n[[File:fanos.jpg|thumb|''Fanos'', an old carnival custom of [[Kozani]]]]\n{{Main|Macedonian cuisine (Greek)}}\n\nMacedonian cuisine is the [[cuisine]] of the region of Macedonia in northern [[Greece]]. Contemporary Greek Macedonian cooking shares much with general [[Greek cuisine|Greek]] and wider [[Balkan cuisine|Balkan]] and [[Mediterranean cuisine|Mediterranean]] cuisine, including dishes from the [[Ottoman cuisine|Ottoman]] past. Specific influences include dishes of the [[Pontic Greeks|Pontic]], [[Aromanians|Aromanian]], [[Armenians|Armenian]] and [[Jews of Thessaloniki|Sephardi Jewish]] population. The mix of the different people inhabiting the region gave the name to the ''[[Macedonian salad]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iefimerida.gr/news/385886/i-koyzina-tis-makedonias-vazei-ypopsifiotita-gia-toys-katalogoys-tis-unesco|title=\u0397 \u03ba\u03bf\u03c5\u03b6\u03af\u03bd\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b2\u03ac\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03c5\u03c0\u03bf\u03c8\u03b7\u03c6\u03b9\u03cc\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 Unesco|last=iefimerida.gr|date=29 December 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Macedonian music===\n{{Main|Music of Macedonia (Greece)}}\n\nMusic of Macedonia is the [[music]] of the geographic region of Macedonia in [[Greece]], which is a part of the [[Music of Macedonia (Greece)|music]] of whole [[Macedonia (region)|region of Macedonia]]. Notable element of the local folk music is the use of [[trumpets]] and [[koudounia]] (called ''ch\u00e1lkina'' in the local dialect).\n\n==Demographics==\n[[File:Population pyramid of Macedonia (Greece).svg|thumb|240px|[[Population pyramid]] of Macedonia from the 2011 census]]\n\nIn 2011 the permanent population of the region stood at 2,406,393 residents,<ref name=\"census 2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gr/documents/20181/1210503/resident_population_census2011rev.xls |title=\u03a0\u03af\u03bd\u03b1\u03ba\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03c4\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03c3\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u039c\u039f\u039d\u0399\u039c\u039f\u03a5 \u03a0\u03bb\u03b7\u03b8\u03c5\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03cd{{endash}}\u0391\u03c0\u03bf\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03ae\u03c2 2011 |trans-title=Table of results of the PERMANENT Population{{endash}}Census 2011 |publisher=Hellenic Statistical Authority |work=[[Greek census 2011]] |year=2011 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> a decrease from 2,422,533 in 2001.<ref name=\"census 2001\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gr |title=National Statistical Service of Greece |work=NSSG |publisher=statistics.gr |year=2001 |accessdate=2007-12-26 }} {{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gr/gr_tables/S1101_SAP_1_TB_DC_01_03_Y.pdf |title=2001 census |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090318065626/http://www.statistics.gr/gr_tables/S1101_SAP_1_TB_DC_01_03_Y.pdf |archivedate=2009-03-18 }}</ref> As of 2017, the population of Macedonia is estimated to have further decreased to 2,382,857.<ref name=\"Mac Pop 2017\" /> In the [[Greek census 2011|2011 Greek census]] the capital city, [[Thessaloniki]], had an urban population of 824,676, up from 794,330 in 2001,<ref name=\"census 2001\" /> while its metropolitan population increased to over a million.<ref name=\"census 2011\" /> 281,458 people in Macedonia (or 12% of the population) were born in a foreign country, compared to 11.89% for the whole of Greece.<ref name=\"census 2011 nationality\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gr/el/statistics?p_p_id=documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ&p_p_lifecycle=2&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_cacheability=cacheLevelPage&p_p_col_id=column-2&p_p_col_count=4&p_p_col_pos=2&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_javax.faces.resource=document&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_ln=downloadResources&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_documentID=310564&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_locale=el |title=\u039202. \u039c\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bb\u03b7\u03b8\u03c5\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf \u03b3\u03ad\u03bd\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2 (\u0394\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2, \u03c7\u03ce\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b5\u03be\u03c9\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd){{endash}}\u0394\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf\u03b9 |trans-title=B02. Permanent population by place of birth (Municipality, foreign country){{endash}}Municipalities |publisher=Hellenic Statistical Authority |work=[[Greek census 2011]] |year=2011 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> 51.32% of the population was female, and 48.68% male.<ref name=\"census 2011 sex and age groups\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gr/el/statistics?p_p_id=documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ&p_p_lifecycle=2&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_cacheability=cacheLevelPage&p_p_col_id=column-2&p_p_col_count=4&p_p_col_pos=2&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_javax.faces.resource=document&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_ln=downloadResources&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_documentID=310563&_documents_WAR_publicationsportlet_INSTANCE_VBZOni0vs5VJ_locale=el |title=\u039201. \u039c\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bb\u03b7\u03b8\u03c5\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03c6\u03cd\u03bb\u03bf, \u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03b4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03b7\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03b9\u03ce\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf \u03b3\u03ad\u03bd\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2 (\u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c6\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ae \u03b5\u03bd\u03cc\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b1, \u03c7\u03ce\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b5\u03be\u03c9\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd){{endash}}\u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c6\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u0395\u03bd\u03cc\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 |trans-title=B01. Permanent population by sex, age groups, and place of birth (regional unit, foreign country){{endash}}Regional units|publisher=Hellenic Statistical Authority |work=[[Greek census 2011]] |year=2011 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> Like the rest of Greece Macedonia is faced with an aging population; the largest age group in the region is that of the over 70, at 15.59% of the population, while the 0-9 and 10-19 groups combined made up 20.25% of the population.<ref name=\"census 2011 sex and age groups\" /> The largest urban centers in Macedonia in 2011 were:\n\n{{Largest cities\n| name        = Largest cities in Macedonia <!-- THIS LIST IS FOR CITIES, NOT FOR MUNICIPALITIES. IT ONLY LISTS URBAN AREAS. THAT IS TO SAY THE SMALLEST SUBDIVISION RECORDED IN THE CENSUS, NOT THE ENTIRE MUNICIPAL POPULATION EACH CITY IS THE ADMINISTRATIVE CENTRE FOR. -->\n| class       = nav\n| country     = Macedonia (Greece)\n| kind        = cities and towns\n| stat_ref    = [[Greek census 2011]]<ref name=\"census 2011\" />\n| list_by_pop = \n| div_name    = \n| div_link    = \n\n| city_1      = Thessaloniki\n| div_1       = \n| pop_1       = 824,676<ref>Thessaloniki is an urban area defined in 1985 through Law 1561/1985. Since the [[Kallikratis Plan|Kallikratis reform]] it has been made up of the municipalities of Thessaloniki (325,182), Kalamaria (91,518), Neapoli{{endash}}Sykies (84,741), Pavlos Melas (99,245), Kordelio{{endash}}Evosmos (101,753), Ampelokipoi{{endash}}Menemeni (52,127), and the municipal units of Pylaia and Panorama (34,625 and 17,444; part of the municipality of Pylaia{{endash}}Chortiatis). The Thessaloniki metropolitan area was defined by the same law and is made up of the Urban area plus the municipalities of Delta (45,839), Oraiokastro (38,317), Thermaikos (50,264), Thermi (53,201), and the municipal unit of Chortiatis (18,041; part of the municipality of Pylaia{{endash}}Chortiatis), for a total of 1,030,338. See {{Cite web |url=http://www.et.gr/idocs-nph/search/pdfViewerForm.html?args=5C7QrtC22wHO1H1f3wMBQHdtvSoClrL8xsqFXEcDVXt5MXD0LzQTLWPU9yLzB8V68knBzLCmTXKaO6fpVZ6Lx9hLslJUqeiQYnJ0rXgB9l_ZIK4zLb8ji7AGLfboDNaz61qOy2y3UGw. |script-title=el:\u0395\u03c6\u03b7\u03bc\u03b5\u03c1\u03af\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03c5\u03b2\u03b5\u03c1\u03bd\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03c9\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 |date=6 September 1985 |publisher=National Printing House |location=Athens |page=2332 |language=Greek |trans-title=[[Government Gazette (Greece)|Government Gazette]] of the Hellenic Republic |access-date=10 February 2019}}</ref>\n| img_1 = Salonica-view-aerial.jpg\n| city_2 = Serres | div_2 =  | pop_2 = 58,287 | img_2 = Serres overview.jpg\n| city_3 = Katerini | div_3 = | pop_3 = 55,997 | img_3 = Street in Katerini, Greece.jpg\n| city_4 = Kavala | div_4 = | pop_4 = 54,027 | img_4 = Kavalapanorama.jpg\n| city_5 = Drama (Greece){{!}}Drama | div_5 =  | pop_5 = 44,823\n| city_6 = Veria | div_6 =  | pop_6 = 43,158\n| city_7 = Kozani | div_7 =  | pop_7 = 41,066\n| city_8 = Ptolemaida | div_8 =  | pop_8 = 32,127\n| city_9 = Giannitsa | div_9 =  | pop_9 = 29,789\n| city_10 = Kilkis | div_10 = | pop_10 = 22,914\n| city_11 = Oraiokastro | div_11 = | pop_11 = 20,852\n| city_12 = Naousa, Imathia{{!}}Naousa | div_12 = | pop_12 = 18,882\n| city_13 = Peraia, Thessaloniki{{!}}Peraia | div_13 = | pop_13 = 18,326\n| city_14 = Edessa | div_14 = | pop_14 = 18,229\n| city_15 = Florina | div_15 = | pop_15 = 14,279\n| city_16 = Thermi | div_16 = | pop_16 = 16,004\n| city_17 = Alexandria, Greece{{!}}Alexandria | div_17 = | pop_17 = 17,686\n| city_18 = Kastoria | div_18 = | pop_18 = 13,387\n| city_19 = Grevena | div_19 = | pop_19 = 13,137\n| city_20 = Diavata | div_20 = | pop_20 = 9,890\n}}\n\n===Demographic history===\n{{See also|Demographic history of Macedonia}}\n[[file:Ethnic map of Balkans - german 1882.jpg|thumb|Ethnic map of the [[Balkan]]s in 1882, showing the mix of nationalities in Macedonia]]\n\nThe inhabitants of Greek Macedonia are nowadays overwhelmingly ethnic [[Greeks]], and most are also [[Greek Orthodox Church|Greek Orthodox]] [[Christians]]. From the Middle Ages to the early 20th century, the [[Demographic history of Macedonia|ethnic composition of the region of Macedonia]] is characterized by uncertainty both about numbers and identification. The earliest estimation we have is from the Greek consulate of [[Thessaloniki]] in 1884, which according to it the nowadays Greek region of Macedonia had 1,073,000 Greeks (Grecophones, Slavophones, Albanophones), 565,000 [[Muslims]], 215,000 [[Bulgarians]] and 16,000 [[Aromanians]].<ref>AYE, Consulates of Macedonia, Thessaloniki, 8th February 1884, no.171.</ref> The 1904 [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] census of Hilmi Pasha people were assigned to ethnicity according which church/language they belonged, it recorded 373,227 Greeks in the [[vilayet of Sel\u00e2nik]] ([[Thessaloniki]]), 261,283 Greeks in the [[vilayet of Monastir]] ([[Bitola]]) and 13,452 Greeks in the [[Kosovo Vilayet|villayet of Kosovo]].<ref name=Gillespie89>{{cite book|last=Gillespie|first=Richard|title=Mediterranean politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UpC4QJP66HUC&lpg=PP1&dq=el&pg=PA89#v=onepage&q=&f=false|publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press|page=89|year=1994|isbn=0-8386-3609-8}}</ref> Of those 648,962 Greeks by church, 307,000 identified as Greek speakers, while about 250,000 as Slavic speakers and 99,000 as [[Vlach language|Vlach]].<ref name=\"Shaw\">{{cite book|last1=Shaw|first1=Stanford|last2=Shaw|first2=Ezel|title=History of the Ottoman Empire and Modern Turkey: Volume 2, Reform, Revolution, and Republic: The Rise of Modern Turkey 1808\u20131975|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-29166-8|page=208|edition=11|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AIET_7ji7YAC&pg=PA208|date=1977-05-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Hodge|first1=Carl|title=Encyclopedia of the Age of Imperialism, 1800\u20131914|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-04341-3|page=631|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y5zTkGKy4wEC&pg=PA631|year=2008}}</ref> However, these figures extend to territories both inside and outside of Greek Macedonia. Hugh Poulton, in his ''Who Are the Macedonians'', notes that \"assessing population figures is problematic\"<ref name=\"poulton\">{{cite book |first=Hugh |last=Poulton |year=2000 |title=Who Are the Macedonians? |chapter=Greece |editor=Second |pages=85\u201386 |publisher=Indiana University Press |isbn=0-253-21359-2 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=8_zeaeTOz6YC&pg=PA85&lpg=PA85&dq=85 }}</ref> for the territory of Greek Macedonia before its incorporation into the Greek state in 1913.<ref name=\"poulton\" /> The area's remaining population was principally composed of [[Ottoman Turks]] (including non-Turkish Muslims of mainly Bulgarian and Greek Macedonian convert origin) and also a sizable community of mainly [[Sephardic Jews]] (centered in Thessaloniki), and smaller numbers of [[Romani people|Romani]], [[Albanians]] and [[Vlachs]].\n\nWhen Macedonia was first incorporated in Greece in 1913, however, Greeks were a marginal plurality in the region.<ref name=\"Greece, Dimitri Pentzopoulos page 134\"/> The treaties of [[Treaty of Neuilly|Neuilly]] (1919) and [[Treaty of Lausanne|Lausanne]] (1923) mandated a forceful exchange of populations with Bulgaria and Turkey respectively, and some 776,000 Greek refugees (mostly from Turkey) were resettled in Macedonia,<ref name=\"Greece, Dimitri Pentzopoulos page 134\">The Balkan Exchange of Minorities and Its Impact on Greece, Dimitri Pentzopoulos, page 134, 2002</ref> displacing 300,000{{endash}}400,000 non-Greeks who were forced to move as part of the population exchange.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u039a\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c6\u03c5\u03b3\u03b9\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd \u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03bf\u03b9\u03ba\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03ce\u03bd \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 (Catalogue of Refugee Communities in Greek Macedonia, includung changes in Macedonian place-names |url=http://www.freewebs.com/onoma/eap.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211100900/http://www.freewebs.com/onoma/eap.htm |archivedate=2009-02-11 }}</ref> The population of ethnic minorities in Macedonia dropped from 48% of the total population in 1920 to 12% in 1928, with the [[Great Greek Encyclopedia]] noting in 1934 that those minorities that remained \"do not yet possess a Greek [[national consciousness]]\".<ref name=\"gge\">{{Citation |title=\u1f19\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03c2 - \u1f19\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u1f78\u03c2 |url=http://anemi.lib.uoc.gr/php/pdf_pager.php?filename=%2Fvar%2Fwww%2Fanemi-portal%2Fmetadata%2Fa%2Ff%2Fb%2Fattached-metadata-01-0002588%2F279838_10.pdf&rec=%2Fmetadata%2Fa%2Ff%2Fb%2Fmetadata-01-0002588.tkl&do=279838_10.pdf&width=662&height=963&pagestart=1&maxpage=1104&lang=en&pageno=1&pagenotop=1&pagenobottom=262 |work=\u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7 \u1f18\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u1f74 \u1f18\u03b3\u03ba\u03c5\u03ba\u03bb\u03bf\u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b5\u1fd6\u03b1 |volume=10 |location=Athens |publisher=Pyrsos Co. Ltd. |date=1934 |trans-title=Greece - Hellenism |page=408 }}</ref>\n\nThe population of Macedonia was greatly affected by the [[World War II|Second World War]], as it was militarily occupied by [[Nazi Germany]] while its ally, [[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]], [[annexation|annexed]] eastern Macedonia. Germany administered its occupation zone by implementation of the [[Nuremberg Laws]],<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=GsBtAAAAMAAJ&q=nuremberg+laws+thessaloniki&dq=nuremberg+laws+thessaloniki |title=From Thessaloniki to Auschwitz and Back: Memories of a Survivor from Thessaloniki |last=Kounio-Amarilio |first=Erika |date=2000 |publisher=Vallentine Mitchell |page=41 |language=en |access-date=2019-02-08|isbn=9780853033905 }}</ref> which saw some 43,000{{endash}}49,000 of Thessaloniki's 56,000 Jews exterminated in the [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] and [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp]]s.<ref name=\"atlas of the holocaust\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=pYs5OSnsrHwC&pg=PA152&dq=Salonica#v=onepage&q=Salonica&f=false |title=The Routledge Atlas of the Holocaust |last=Gilbert |first=Martin |date=2002 |publisher=Psychology Press |page=196 |language=en |access-date=2019-02-08|isbn=9780415281454 }}</ref><ref name=\"Exodus\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/expulsionofjews00stro|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/expulsionofjews00stro/page/102 102]|quote=jews of thessaloniki.|title=The Expulsion of the Jews: Five Hundred Years of Exodus|publisher=SP Books|author=Yale Strom|year=1992|accessdate=13 September 2018|isbn=9781561710812}}</ref><ref name=\"Times of Israel\">{{cite web |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/thessalonikis-new-holocaust-museum-a-sign-of-a-city-finally-embracing-its-jewish-past/ |title=Thessaloniki's new Holocaust museum a sign of a city finally embracing its Jewish past |website=www.timesofisrael.com |publisher=[[The Times of Israel]] |language=en-US |access-date=2018-09-13}}</ref> In its own zone of annexation, Bulgaria actively persecuted the local Greek population with the help of Bulgarian collaborationists.<ref name=\"loring\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZmesOn_HhfEC&pg=PA41&dq=bulgaria+macedonia+ww2+greece#v=onepage&q=bulgaria%2520macedonia%2520ww2%2520greece&f=false |title=The Macedonian Conflict: Ethnic Nationalism in a Transnational World |last=Danforth |first=Loring M. |date=1997-04-06 |publisher=Princeton University Press |page=41 |language=en |access-date=2019-02-08|isbn=0691043566 }}</ref> Further demographic change happened in the aftermath of the [[Greek Civil War]], when many Slavs of Macedonia who fought on the side of the [[Democratic Army of Greece]] and fought to separate Greek Macedonia from the rest of Greece under the auspices of [[Yugoslavia]], left Greece.<ref name=\"loring\" /> These expatriates were the primary source of [[United Macedonia|ethnic Macedonian irredentism]] and the appropriation of ancient Macedonian heritage.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=4TjZXtwnkncC&pg=PA23&dq=greek+macedonians+regional+identity#v=onepage&q=greek%2520macedonians%2520regional%2520identity&f=false |title=Waiting for Macedonia: Identity in a Changing World |last=Thiessen |first=Ilk\u00e1 |date=2007 |publisher=University of Toronto Press |page=25 |language=en |access-date=2019-02-08|isbn=9781551117195 }}</ref>\n\n===Regional identity===\n{{Main|Macedonians (Greeks)}}\n[[File:Apogevmatini Macedonians.gif|thumb|180px|[[Apogevmatini]] headline quoting [[Kostas Karamanlis]]:<br/>\"I myself am a Macedonian, just as 2.5 million Greeks.\"]]\n[[File:Georgios Tiligadis.jpg|thumb|160px|A man in ''[[Macedonian Struggle|Macedonomachos]]'' uniform]]\n\nMacedonians ({{lang-el|\u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03cc\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2|translit=Makedh\u00f3nes}}) is the term by which ethnic [[Greeks]] originating from the region are known.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mfa.gr/en/fyrom-name-issue/ |title=FYROM Name Issue |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Greece)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] |location=Athens |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714153923/https://www.mfa.gr/en/fyrom-name-issue/ |archive-date=2018-07-14 |url-status=dead |access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref><ref name=\"osce\">{{Cite book |url=https://www.osce.org/cio/68840?download=true |title=Mission to Greece |last=McDougall |first=Gay |work=Promotion and protection of all human rights, civil, political, economic, social and cultural rights, including the right to development: Report of the independent expert on minority issues, Gay McDougall |publisher=[[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] |year=2008 |location=New York |language=en}}</ref> Macedonians came to be of particular importance prior to the [[Balkan Wars]], during the [[Macedonian Struggle]], when they were a minority population inside the multiethnic [[Ottoman Greece|Ottoman Macedonia]]. The Macedonians now have a strong regional identity, manifested both in Greece and by emigrant groups in the [[Greek diaspora]].<ref name=Liotta>{{cite web|last1=Liotta |first1=P. H. |last2=Simons |first2=A. |url=http://www.carlisle.army.mil/usawc/parameters/98winter/liotta.htm |title=Thicker than Water? Kin, Religion, and Conflict in the Balkans |work=Parameters (Winter 1998) |pages=11\u201327 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061125163221/http://www.carlisle.army.mil/usawc/parameters/98winter/liotta.htm |archivedate=2006-11-25 }}</ref><ref name=\"theaustralianpeople\">[[James Jupp|Jupp, J.]] ''The Australian People: An Encyclopedia of the Nation, Its People and Their Origins'', [[Cambridge University Press]], October 1, 2001. {{ISBN|0-521-80789-1}}, p. 147.</ref> This sense of identity has been highlighted in the context of the [[Macedonia naming dispute]] in the aftermath of the [[Breakup of Yugoslavia|break-up of Yugoslavia]], in which Greece objected to its northern neighbor calling itself the \"[[Republic of Macedonia]]\". This objection is the direct result of this regional identity, and a matter of heritage for northern Greeks.<ref>Floudas, Demetrius Andreas; {{cite news |publisher= 24 (1996) Journal of Political and Military Sociology, 285|url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3719/is_199601/ai_n8752910 | title= A Name for a Conflict or a Conflict for a Name? An Analysis of Greece's Dispute with FYROM\" |accessdate=2008-02-11 | year=1996}}</ref> A characteristic expression of this self-identification was manifested by [[List of Prime Ministers of Greece|Prime Minister]] [[Kostas Karamanlis]] at a meeting of the [[Council of Europe]] in [[Strasbourg]] in January 2007, declaring that \"I myself am a Macedonian, and another two and a half million Greeks are Macedonians\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.naftemporiki.gr/story/181305/karamanlisego-o-idios-eimai-makedonas-kathos-kai-25-ekatommuria-ellines |script-title=el:\u039a\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03bc\u03b1\u03bd\u03bb\u03ae\u03c2:\"\u0395\u03b3\u03ce \u03bf \u03af\u03b4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b5\u03af\u03bc\u03b1\u03b9 \u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03cc\u03bd\u03b1\u03c2, \u03ba\u03b1\u03b8\u03ce\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 2,5 \u03b5\u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03bc\u03bc\u03cd\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1 \u0388\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2...\" |date=2007-01-24 |website=www.naftemporiki.gr |language=el |access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\nIn the early-to-mid [[20th century]] Greece was invaded by [[Bulgaria]] three times with the aim of capturing portions Macedonia;<ref name=\"roudometof\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Xoww453NVQMC&pg=PA75&dq=greek+macedonians+regional+identity#v=onepage&q=greek%2520macedonians%2520regional%2520identity&f=false |title=Collective Memory, National Identity, and Ethnic Conflict: Greece, Bulgaria, and the Macedonian Question |last=Roudometof |first=Victor |date=2002 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |language=en |access-date=2019-02-13|isbn=9780275976484 }}</ref> during the [[Second Balkan War]], during the [[First World War]], and during the [[Second World War]]. Additionally, [[Nazi Germany]] had promised [[Thessaloniki]] to [[Yugoslavia]] as a reward for joining the [[Axis powers]].<ref name=\"Thessaloniki En Thermo Yugoslavia\">{{cite book|last=Panagiotopoulos|first=Apostolos|title=\u0398\u03b5\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03ba\u03b7&nbsp;... \u03b5\u03bd \u0398\u03b5\u03c1\u03bc\u03ce \u2013 \u039f \u03c3\u03c5\u03b3\u03ba\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 20\u03cc\u03c2 \u03b1\u03b9\u03ce\u03bd\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2|trans-title=Thessaloniki&nbsp;... on Fire \u2013 The City's Sensational 20th Century|publisher=Maliaris Paideia|year=2009|isbn=978-960-457-239-7|volume=B|page=738}}</ref> The perceived existence of a foreign danger had a particularly strong effect on the emergence of a distinct regional identity in Macedonia.<ref name=\"roudometof\" /> The representation of the [[Macedonian Struggle]] in [[Penelope Delta]]'s popular 1937 [[Young adult fiction|teen novel]] {{em|Secrets of the Swamp}} solidified the image of the [[chauvinism|chauvinist]] clash between Greeks and Bulgarians in Macedonia in the minds of many Greeks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://books.google.com/?id=4vtQAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT60&dq=makedones#v=onepage&q=chauvinist%2520representation&f=false |title=Dialogos: Hellenic Studies Review |last=Ricks |first=David |last2=Trapp |first2=Michael |date=2014-04-08 |publisher=Routledge |language=en |access-date=2019-02-16}}</ref> Bulgaria was specifically mentioned as the enemy in Greek Macedonia's unofficial anthem, [[Famous Macedonia]], the reference only being replaced by vague 'Barbarians' with the normalization of Greco-Bulgarian relations in the 1970s.<ref name=\"roudometof\" /> During the same period, [[Manolis Andronikos]] made major [[archaeology|archaeological]] discoveries at [[Vergina|Aigai]], the first capital of [[Macedonia (ancient kingdom)|ancient Macedonia]], which included the tomb of [[Philip II of Macedon|Phillip II]], [[Alexander the Great]]'s father.<ref name=\"borza\">{{Cite journal |last=Borza |first=Eugene N. |title=Manolis Andronikos, 1919-1992 |journal=[[American Journal of Archaeology]] |volume=96 |issue=4 |pages=757\u2013758 |jstor=505193 |year=1992 }}</ref> His discoveries were drawn upon as evidence of ethnic and cultural links between the [[ancient Macedonians]] and southern [[Polis|Greek city-states]]<ref name=\"borza\" /><ref name=\"osce\" /> by Greeks in Macedonia.\n\nThe distinct regional identity of Greek Macedonians is also the product of the fact that it was closer to the centers of power in both the [[Byzantine]] and [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] period, was considered culturally, politically, and strategically more important than other parts of Greece during these two periods, and also the fact that the region had a far more ethnically and religiously diverse population in both the medieval and Ottoman periods. In the late Byzantine period Greek Macedonia had also been the centre of significant Byzantine successor states, such as the [[Kingdom of Thessalonica]], the short-lived state established by the rival Byzantine emperor, [[Theodore Komnenos Doukas]], and - in parts of western Macedonia - the [[Despotate of Epirus]], all of which helped promote a distinct Greek Macedonian identity.\n\nIn the contemporary period this is reinforced by Greek Macedonia's proximity to other states in the southern Balkans, the continuing existence of ethnic and religious minorities in [[Eastern Macedonia and Thrace]] not found in southern Greece, and the fact that migrants and refugees from elsewhere in the Balkans, southern Russia, and Georgia (including [[Pontic Greeks]] and [[Caucasus Greeks]] from northeastern [[Anatolia]] and the [[south Caucasus]]) have usually gravitated to Greek Macedonia rather than southern Greece.\n\n===Languages and minorities===\n{{details|Minorities in Greece}}\n{{See also|Aromanians in Greece|Arvanites|Megleno-Romanians}}\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = South-Balkan-Romance-languages.png\n| width1 = 150\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Vlahomeglen-map-en.png\n| width2 = 150\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = Right: The Megleno-Romanian and the Aromanian linguistic area.<br/> Left: Map of the Megleno-Romanians settlements.\n}}\n[[Greek language|Greek]] is the majority language throughout Greece today, with an estimated 5% of the population speaking a language other than Greek,<ref name=\"europarl lang\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/document_travail/educ/2002/0108/04A-EDUC_DT(2002)0108_EN.doc |title=The European Union and Lesser-Used Languages |last=Becat |first=Joan |last2=Christopoulos |first2=Dimitris |last3=Lainio |first3=Jarmo |last4=Lepr\u00eatre |first4=Marc |last5=Nelde |first5=Peter |last6=O Riagain |first6=Padraig |last7=Strubell |first7=Antoni |last8=Tsitselikis |first8=Constantinos |last9=Vernet |first9=Jaume |last10=Vilar\u00f3 |first10=Sergi |last11=Villalonga |first11=Aina |last12=Weber |first12=Nico |last13=Weber |first13=Peter |last14=Williams |first14=Glyn |date=July 2002 |work=Education and Culture Series |series=EDUC 108 EN |publisher=[[European Parliament]] |language=en |format=DOC |location=[[Luxembourg]] |access-date=16 February 2019}}</ref> and is the only language of administration and education in the region. Greek is spoken universally in Greek Macedonia, even in the border regions where there is a strong presence of languages other than Greek.<ref name=\"riki\">{{Cite web |url=http://journals.openedition.org/strates/381 |title=Usage des langues minoritaires dans les d\u00e9partements de Florina et d'Aridea (Mac\u00e9doine) |last=Van Boeschoten |first=Riki |date=1 May 2005 |website=www.journals. |publisher=Strates {{emdash}} Mat\u00e9riaux pour la recherche en sciences sociales |language=fr |trans-title=Use of minority languages in the regions of Florina and Aridea (Macedonia) |issn=0768-8067 |access-date=16 February 2019}}</ref> The Greek government exhibits some tolerance toward the use of minority languages,<ref name=\"europarl lang\" /> though Greece is one of the countries which has not signed the [[European Charter for Regional and Minority Languages]];<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/EPRS/EPRS-Briefing-589794-Regional-minority-languages-EU-FINAL.pdf |title=Regional and minority languages in the European Union |last=Pasikowska-Schnass |first=Magdalena |date=September 2016 |series=PE 589.794 |publisher=[[European Parliament|European Parliamentary Research Service]] |access-date=16 February 2019}}</ref> a number of court cases have been brought to the attention of the [[European Parliament]] regarding the suppression of minority linguistic rights.<ref name=\"europarl lang\" />\n\nApart from Standard Modern Greek, a number of other [[Varieties of Modern Greek#Spoken dialects|Greek dialects]] are spoken in Macedonia. This includes [[Pontic Greek]], a language spoken originally on the shores of the [[Black Sea]] in northeastern [[Anatolia]] and the [[Caucasus]], as well as an archaic Greek dialect indigenous to Greek Macedonia and other parts of Northern Greece known as {{Lang|el-Latn|Sarakats\u00e1nika}} ({{lang-el|\u03a3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03c3\u03ac\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03b1}}). This dialect is spoken by the [[Sarakatsani]], a traditionally [[Transhumance|transhumant]] shepherd Greek community whose spoken tongue has undergone very little change through foreign influences.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Katsaros|first=Nikos|script-title=el:\u039f\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c1\u03c7\u03b1\u03b9\u03bf\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03c1\u03af\u03b6\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03c3\u03ac\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf\u03c5|trans-title=Ancient Greek roots of the Sarakatsanika tongue|publisher=I.Sideris|location=Athens|year=1995|language=Greek}}</ref>\n\nMacedonia is also home to an array of non-Greek languages. [[Slavic languages]] are the most prevalent minority languages in the region, while [[Aromanian language|Aromanian]], [[Arvanitic language|Arvanitic]], [[Megleno-Romanian language|Megleno-Romanian]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]], and [[Romani language|Romani]] are also spoken. [[Judaeo-Spanish]], also known as {{em|Ladino}}, was historically the language of the Jewish community of Thessaloniki, although [[the Holocaust]] nearly eradicated the city's previously-vibrant Jewish community of 70,000 to a mere 3,000 individuals today.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Stavroulakis |first=Nicholas |date=Autumn 2003 |journal=European Judaism: A Journal for the New Europe |volume=36 |issue=2 |pages=34\u201340 |jstor=41443650 |doi=10.3167/001430003782266107|title=The Jewish Museum of Thessaloniki - Museo Djidio di Salonik }}</ref>\n\n[[File:199 Neveska View from the Church.jpg|thumb|180px|The Aromanian (Vlach) village of [[Nymfaio]], example of traditional architecture]]\n\nThe exact size of the linguistic and ethnic minority groups in Macedonia is not known with any degree of scientific accuracy, as Greece has not conducted a census on the question of mother tongue since 1951. Aromanians form a minority population throughout much of Macedonia. They largely identify as Greeks and most belong to the Greek Orthodox Church, refusing to be called a minority group.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=2002 |title=Jahrb\u00fccher f\u00fcr Geschichte und Kultur S\u00fcdosteuropasYearbooks for History and Culture of Southeastern Europe |url=https://books.google.com/?id=HFAsAQAAIAAJ |journal=Slavica Verlag |language=de |trans-title=}}</ref> In the 1951 census they numbered 39,855 in all Greece (the number in Macedonia proper is unknown). Many Aromanian villages can be found along the slopes of the [[Vermion Mountains]] and [[Mount Olympus]]. Smaller numbers can be found in the [[Prespes]] region and near the [[Gramos]] mountains. Megleno-Romanians can be found in the [[Moglena]] region of Macedonia. The [[Megleno-Romanian language]] is traditionally spoken in the 11 Vlach villages spread across Greece and the [[North Macedonia|Republic of North Macedonia]], including [[Archangelos, Pella|Archangelos]], [[Notia]], [[Lagkadia, Pella|Lagkadia]], and [[Skra, Kilkis|Skra]]. They are generally adherents to the Orthodox Church while the former majority in Notia was Muslim. Arvanite communities exist in [[Serres (regional unit)|Serres regional unit]], while many can also be found in Thessaloniki. There are three Arvanite villages in the Florina regional unit ([[Drosopigi, Florina|Drosopigi]], [[Lechovo]] and [[Flampouro, Florina|Flampouro]]) with others located in Kilkis and Thessaloniki regional units.<ref name = Arvanites>Euromosaic (1996): \"L'arvanite / albanais en Gr\u00e8ce\". Report published by the Institut de Socioling\u00fc\u00edstica Catalana.</ref> Other minority groups include [[Armenians]] and [[Romani people|Romani]]. Romani communities are concentrated mainly around the city of Thessaloniki. An uncertain number of them live in Macedonia from the total of about 200,000\u2013300,000 that live scattered on all [[Roma in Greece|the regions of Greece]].<ref name=NCHR-Roma>{{cite web|url=http://www.nchr.gr/category.php?category_id%3D99 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070914020127/http://www.nchr.gr/category.php?category_id=99 |archivedate=2007-09-14 }}</ref>\n\n====Ethnic Macedonian minority and language====\n{{Main|Slavic-speakers of Greek Macedonia}}\n[[File:Linguistic minorities in Florina and Aridaia.svg|thumb|Distribution of the [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]] and other languages in the Florina and Aridaia regions of Greek Macedonia]]\n\nThe [[Macedonian language]], a member of the [[South Slavic languages]] closely related to [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]], is today spoken mostly in the [[regional units of Greece|regional units]] of [[Florina (regional unit)|Florina]] and [[Pella (regional unit)|Pella]].<ref name=\"europarl lang\" /> Due to the sensitivity of the use of term 'Macedonian', the language is [[euphemism|euphemistically]] referred to as {{Lang|el|\u03bd\u03c4\u03cc\u03c0\u03b9\u03b1}} ({{Lang|el-Latn|d\u00f3pia}}, \"local\") or {{em|nasi}} ({{lang-mk|\u043d\u0430\u0448\u0438 or na\u0161i}}, 'our (language)').<ref name=\"europarl lang\" />\n\nThe exact number of the minority is difficult to know as Greece has not collected data on languages as part of its census since 1951. The 1928 census listed 81,984 speakers of 'Slavomacedonian' in Greece,<ref>{{citation |title=\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u1f74 \u1f19\u03c0\u03b5\u03c4\u03b7\u03c1\u1f76\u03c2 \u03c4\u1fc6\u03c2 \u1f19\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2{{endash}}1936 |date=May 1937 |url=http://dlib.statistics.gr/Book/GRESYE_01_0002_00006.pdf |editor-last=Michalopoulos |editor-first=Ioannis G. |publisher=[[Hellenic Statistical Authority]] |place=Athens |trans-title=Statistical Yearbook of Greece{{endash}}1936 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831215924/http://dlib.statistics.gr/Book/GRESYE_01_0002_00006.pdf |archive-date=31 August 2018 |language=Greek, French |page=71}}</ref> but internal government documents from the 1930s put the number of Macedonian speakers in the Florina prefecture alone at 80,000 or 61% of the population.<ref name=\"Danforth\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZmesOn_HhfEC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=Abecedar&f=false |title=The Macedonian Conflict: Ethnic Nationalism in a Transnational World |last=Danforth |first=Loring M. |date=1997-04-06 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=069-104-356-6 |pages=69\u201372}}</ref> A [[field research|field study]] conducted in 1993 in these two regions under the auspices of the [[European Parliament]] found that of the 74 villages studied, Macedonian was spoken in various degrees of vitality in 49 villages and was the primary language in 15 villages.<ref name=\"riki\" /> To a lesser extent Macedonian is also present in the regional units of [[Kastoria (regional unit)|Kastoria]], [[Imathia]], [[Kilkis (regional unit)|Kilkis]], [[Thessaloniki (regional unit)|Thessaloniki]], [[Serres (regional unit)|Serres]], and [[Drama (regional unit)|Drama]].<ref name=\"europarl lang\" /> The [[Greek language]] remains dominant in all regions, even in those where Macedonian and other minority languages are present.<ref name=\"riki\" /> The total number of 'slavic speakers' in Greece is estimated to range between as low as 10,000 and as high as 300,000.<ref name=\"transnational\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gate.net/~mango/Danforth_National_Conflict.htm |title=National Conflict in a Transnational World: Greeks and Macedonians at the CSCE |first=Loring M. |last=Danforth |year=1994 |publisher=Gate.net |accessdate=2019-02-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924020829/http://www.gate.net/~mango/Danforth_National_Conflict.htm |archive-date=2015-09-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=InyEqBVhH-EC&pg=PA6&dq=Shea,+John+(1992).+The+Real+Macedonians#PPA125,M1 |title=Macedonia and Greece: The Struggle to Define a New Balkan Nation - John Shea - Google Books |date=1994-11-15 |accessdate=2019-02-19|isbn=9780786402281 |last1=Shea |first1=John }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2001/eur/8261.htm |title=Greece |publisher=State.gov |date=2002-03-04 |accessdate=2019-02-19}}</ref>\n\nGreece has had varied policies toward the Macedonian language throughout its history. In 1925 the Greek government introduced the first Macedonian [[alphabet book]], known as the {{em|[[Abecedar]]}}, based on the Florina dialect of the language;<ref name=\"Danforth\" /> this never entered classrooms due to opposition from Serbia and Bulgaria, as well as an outcry against it in Greece.<ref name=\"Danforth\" /> Efforts to assimilate resulted in instances of populations rejecting their Slavic language, as in the village of Atropos in 1959, where the villagers took \"the oath before God\" to cease speaking the local Slavic idiom and to only speak Greek.<ref name=\"Danforth\" /> Though the Macedonian language has survived despite efforts by Greek authorities to [[Cultural assimilation|assimilate]] the population into the Greek majority, the vast number of Macedonian speakers possess a Greek [[national consciousness]].<ref name=\"europarl lang\" /><ref name=\"helsinki\">{{cite web|url=http://dev.eurac.edu:8085/mugs2/do/blob.html?type=html&serial=1044526702223 |title=Greece &ndash; Report about Compliance with the Principles of the Framework Convention for the Protection of National Minorities (along guidelines for state reports according to Article 25.1 of the Convention) |date=1999-09-18 |work=Greek Helsinki Monitor (GHM) & Minority Rights Group &ndash; Greece (MRG-G) |accessdate=2009-01-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030523145306/http://dev.eurac.edu:8085/mugs2/do/blob.html?type=html&serial=1044526702223 |archivedate=2003-05-23 }}</ref> It is difficult to ascertain the number of those with a different national consciousness, but estimates of the number of people within Greece that possess an [[ethnic Macedonians|ethnic Macedonian]] national identity range between 5,000&ndash;30,000.<ref name=\"helsinki\" /><ref name=\"transnational\" />\n\nGreece claims to respect the [[human rights]] of all its citizens, including the rights of individuals to self-identify, but also claims its policy of not recognizing an ethnic Macedonian minority is based \"on solid legal and factual grounds\".<ref name=\"council\">{{Cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/16806db821 |title=Report by Thomas Hammarberg, Commissioner for Human Rights of the Council of Europe, following his visit to Greece on 8{{endash}}10 December 2008 |last=Hammarberg |first=Thomas |date=19 February 2009 |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |location=Strasbourg |language=en}}</ref> However, reports by organizations such as the [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]], the [[Council of Europe]], and the [[United States Department of State]] have all concluded that Greek authorities are actively discriminatory against the existence of a Macedonian language, minority, or national identity,<ref name=\"council\" /><ref name=\"osce\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/humanrightsreport/index.htm?year=2018&dlid=289135#wrapper |title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices for 2018: Greece |publisher=[[United States Department of State]] |location=Washington, DC |language=en |access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref> even if the situation has improved markedly.<ref name=\"osce\" /> An ethnic Macedonian political party, [[Rainbow (Greece)|Rainbow]], has competed in [[elections in Greece|Greek elections]] for the [[European Parliament]] since 1995.<ref name=\"osce\" /> In the [[2019 European Parliament election in Greece|2019 election]] it received 6,364 votes or 0.11% of the national vote and came 35th in the results table, with most its support coming from Florina where it received 3.33% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ekloges.ypes.gr/current/e/home/en/parties/119/ |title=EVROPAIKI ELEFTHERI SYMMACHIA - OURANIO TOXO |publisher=Ministry of Interior |location=Athens |language=en |access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\n====Jews of Thessaloniki and other cities====\n{{Main|History of the Jews of Thessaloniki|Holocaust Museum of Greece}}\n[[File:Salonique, femme juive, 19e si\u00e8cle.jpg|thumb|upright|Jewish woman from Thessaloniki, gravour of late 19th century]]\n\nNorthern Greece has had Jewish communities since ancient times, including the historically-significant and Greek-speaking [[Romaniotes|Romaniote]] community. During the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] era Thessaloniki became the centre of a [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardi]] community which comprised more than half the city's population, as Ottoman authorities invited Jews who had been expelled from [[Kingdom of Castille|Castille]] in the aftermath of the [[Alhambra Decree]] of 1492 to resettle in the Ottoman Empire. The community nicknamed the city {{em|la madre de Israel}} (the mother of Israel)<ref name=\"Holocaust\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ushmm.org/information/exhibitions/online-exhibitions/special-focus/holocaust-in-greece/thessaloniki |publisher=[[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]] |title=Thessaloniki |accessdate=2019-02-22 }}</ref> and {{em|Jerusalem of the Balkans}},<ref>{{cite book |last=Abrams|first= Dennis |year=2009 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=YkKVeMIMOmoC&pg=PA26&dq=sarkozy+jewish#v=onepage&q=sarkozy%20jewish&f=false |title=Nicolas Sarkozy (Modern World Leaders) |publisher= Chelsea House Publishers| page= 26, Library Binding edition |isbn= 978-1-60413-081-2}}</ref> and brought with it the [[Judaeo-Spanish]], or {{em|Ladino}}, language which became the mother tongue of Thessaloniki Jews.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kushner|first=Aviya|title=Is the language of Sephardic Jews, undergoing a revival?|url=http://www.myjewishlearning.com/culture/2/Languages/Other_Jewish_Languages/Ladino/Today.shtml|work=My Jewish Learning|publisher=Ladino Today|accessdate=9 April 2011}}</ref> By the 1680s about 300 families of Sephardi followers of [[Sabbatai Zevi]] had converted to [[Islam]], becoming a sect known as the ''[[D\u00f6nmeh]]'' (converts), and migrated to Thessaloniki, whose population was by that time majority-Jewish. They established an active community that thrived for about 250 years. Many of their descendants later became prominent in trade.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kirsch|first= Adam |url=http://www.tnr.com/book/review/the-other-secret-jews |title=The Other Secret Jews |work= Review of Marc David Baer's ''The D\u00f6nme: Jewish Converts, Muslim Revolutionaries, and Secular Turks |publisher=The New Republic |date= 15 February 2010| accessdate= 21 February 2010}}</ref> Thessaloniki Jews later became pioneers of [[socialism]] and the [[Trade unionism|labour movement]] in Greece.\n\nBetween the 15th and early 20th centuries, Thessaloniki was the only city in [[Europe]] where Jews were a majority of the population.<ref name=\"executive summary\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.holocausteducenter.gr/executive-summary/ |title=Executive Summary |website=www.holocausteducenter.gr |publisher=[[Holocaust Museum of Greece]] |language=en |access-date=2018-09-13}}</ref> The [[Great Thessaloniki Fire of 1917]] destroyed much of the city and left 50,000 Jews homeless.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jmth.gr/web/thejews/pages/pages/history/pages/his.htm |author=Yakov Benmayor |title=History of Jews in Thessaloniki |publisher=Jewish Museum of Thessaloniki |accessdate=2009-01-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081226001725/http://www.jmth.gr/web/thejews/pages/pages/history/pages/his.htm |archivedate=2008-12-26 }}</ref> Many Jews emigrated to the United States, Palestine, and Paris after the loss of their livelihoods, being unable to wait for the government to create a new urban plan for rebuilding, which was eventually done.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Great Fire in Salonica |url=http://www.mlahanas.de/Greece/History/GreatFireInSalonica1917.html |work=Greece History |publisher=Hellenica Website |accessdate=9 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018013408/http://www.mlahanas.de/Greece/History/GreatFireInSalonica1917.html |archivedate=18 October 2011 }}</ref> The aftermath of the [[Greco-Turkish War (1919\u20131922)|Greco-Turkish War]] and the expulsion of Greeks from Turkey saw nearly 100,000 ethnic Greeks resettled in Thessaloniki, reducing the proportion of Jews in the total community. Following the demographic shift, Jews made up about 20% of the city's population.  During the interwar period, Greece granted the Jews the same [[civil rights]] as other Greek citizens.<ref name=\"History\"/> In March 1926, Greece re-emphasised that all citizens of Greece enjoyed equal rights, and a considerable proportion of the city's Jews decided to stay.\n\n[[File:The_Synagogue_in_Veria.jpg|left|thumb|180px|The Jewish [[synagogue]] of [[Veria]]]]\n\nAccording to [[Misha Glenny]], such Greek Jews had largely not encountered \"anti-Semitism as in its North European form\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Glenny |first=Misha |title=The Balkans: Nationalism, War, and the Great Powers 1804{{endash|url=https://archive.org/details/balkansnationali00mish |url-access=registration }}2011 |publisher=Penguin Random House |page=512}}</ref> Though antisemitism was utilized both by the [[Ioannis Metaxas|Metaxas]] dictatorship and by newspapers such as {{em|[[Makedonia (newspaper)|Makedonia]]}} as part of the wider mechanism for identifying leftists, Greek Jews were either neutral or supportive of Metaxas.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=o3vIneSflMcC&pg=PA101&dq=antisemitism+in+greece#v=onepage&q=antisemitism%2520in%2520greece&f=false |title=Greece {{endash}} a Jewish History |last=Fleming |first=K. E. |date=2010-04-04 |publisher=Princeton University Press |language=en |access-date=2019-02-22|isbn=978-0691146126 }}</ref> By the 1940s, the great majority of the Jewish Greek community firmly identified as both Greek and Jewish. [[World War II]] was disastrous for Greek Jews; the [[Battle of Greece]] saw Greek Macedonia occupied by [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]], [[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]], and [[Nazi Germany]], with the latter occupying much of [[Central Macedonia]] and implementing the [[Nuremberg Laws]] against the Jewish population.  Greeks of the Resistance and Italian forces (before 1943) tried to protect the Jews and managed to save some.<ref name=\"Holocaust\"/> In 1943 the Nazis began actions against the Jews in Thessaloniki, forcing them into a [[ghetto]] near the railroad lines and beginning their deportation to [[Nazi concentration camps|concentration camps]] in German-occupied territories. They deported 56,000 of the city's Jews, by use of 19 [[Holocaust train]]s, to [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] and [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]] concentration camps, where 43,000{{endash}}49,000 of them were killed.<ref name=\"atlas of the holocaust\" /><ref name=\"Exodus\" /><ref name=\"Times of Israel\" /> Today, a community of around 1,200 remains in the city.<ref name=\"Holocaust\"/> Communities of descendants of Thessaloniki Jews&nbsp;\u2013 both Sephardic and Romaniote&nbsp;\u2013 live in other areas, mainly the United States and Israel.<ref name=\"Holocaust\"/> Other cities of Greek Macedonia with significant Jewish population (Romaniote or Sephardi) in the past included [[Veria]], [[Kavala]] and [[Kastoria]].\n\n{{-}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Europe|European Union|Greece}}\n*[[Geographic regions of Greece]]\n*[[List of Macedonians (Greek)]]\n*[[Macedonians (Greeks)]]\n*[[Macedonia (region)]]\n*[[Macedonia (terminology)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n*{{Cite journal |title=No Borders, No Nations: Making Greece in Macedonia |last=Agnew |first=John |journal=Annals of the Association of America